# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: machine-learning
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In machine learning, a **neural network** (**NN**) or **neural net**, is a computational model inspired by the structure and functions of biological neural networks.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] A neural network consists of connected units or nodes called *artificial neurons*, which loosely model the neurons in the brain.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Artificial neuron models that mimic biological neurons more closely have also been recently investigated and shown to significantly improve performance.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] These are connected by *edges*, which model the synapses in the brain.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Each artificial neuron receives signals from connected neurons, then processes them and sends a signal to other connected neurons.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The "signal" is a real number, and the output of each neuron is computed by some non-linear function of the totality of its inputs, called the *activation function*.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The strength of the signal at each connection is determined by a *weight*, which adjusts as part of the training process.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Groups of neurons are aggregated into layers.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Each layer performs a transformation on its inputs.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Signals travel from the first layer (the *input layer*) to the last layer (the *output layer*), typically passing through multiple intermediate layers (*hidden layers*).
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] A network is typically called a deep neural network if it has at least two hidden layers.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Deep neural networks are capable of learning sophisticated hierarchical representations.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Training neural networks is a compute-intensive process, accelerated by the use of graphics processing units (GPUs), and large datasets.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Architectural innovations such as convolutional neural networks (CNNs) significantly improved performance in computer vision tasks, while recurrent neural networks (RNNs) enabled modeling of sequential data such as speech and time-series information.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Transformer architectures introduced attention mechanisms that allow neural networks to model long-range dependencies in data and have the basis of large language models.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Artificial neural networks are used for a myriad of tasks including chatbots, large-scale text, image, and video generation, and robotics.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The starfish match with a ringed texture and a star outline, whereas most sea urchins match with a striped texture and oval shape.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, the instance of a ring textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The network correctly detects the starfish.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two intermediate nodes.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In addition, a shell that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In reality, textures and outlines would not be represented by single nodes, but rather by associated weight patterns of multiple nodes.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Deep neural networks are based on statistics developed over 200 years ago.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The simplest kind of feedforward neural network (FNN) is a linear network, which consists of a single layer of output nodes with linear activation functions; the inputs are fed directly to the outputs via weights.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The sum of the products of the weights and the inputs is calculated at each node.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The mean squared errors between these calculated outputs and the given target values are minimized by adjusting to the weights.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] This technique is the method of least squares or linear regression.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] It was used to find a rough linear fit to a set of points by Legendre (1805) and Gauss (1795) for the prediction of planetary movement.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Computers are based on John von Neumann's model.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] They execute explicit lists of instructions with access to memory to record their changing state.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Neural networks instead originated from efforts to model information processing in biological systems via connectionism.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Unlike the von Neumann model, connectionist computing does not separate memory and processing.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Warren McCulloch and Walter Pitts (1943) considered a non-learning computational model for neural networks.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] This model paved the way for research to split into one branch focused on biological processes and another focused on artificial intelligence.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] McCulloch and Pitts also developed mathematical models of artificial neurons capable of representing logical functions.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Hebb proposed a learning hypothesis based on neural plasticity that became known as Hebbian learning.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] It was used in many early neural network experiments, such as Rosenblatt's perceptron and the Hopfield network.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Farley and Clark (1954) used computational machines to simulate a Hebbian network.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Other neural networks computational machines were created by Rochester, Holland, Habit and Duda (1956).
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1958, psychologist Frank Rosenblatt described the perceptron, one of the first implemented neural networks, funded by the United States Office of Naval Research.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Joseph (1960) mentioned an earlier perceptron-like device by B.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The first perceptrons did not have adaptive hidden units.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, Joseph (1960) discussed multilayer that did.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Rosenblatt (1962) cited and adopted these ideas, crediting work by H.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, these early efforts did not lead to a working learning algorithm for hidden units, i.e., deep learning.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The perceptron raised public excitement in neural networks, causing the US government to drastically increase funding.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] This contributed to "the Golden Age of AI", fueled by the optimistic claims made by computer scientists regarding the ability of perceptrons to emulate human intelligence.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Artificial neural networks were identified as a promising direction for artificial intelligence research in the 1955 proposal for the Dartmouth Summer Research Project on Artificial Intelligence.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Neural network models initially faced major limitations.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Hardware constraints limited network size and training efficiency, while theoretical understanding of learning algorithms remained incomplete.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Many models used single-layer perceptrons, which were restricted to solving linearly separable problems.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] These limitations were highlighted in the book *Perceptrons* by Marvin Minsky and Seymour Papert, which deflated interest during the late 1960s and 1970s.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Fundamental research was conducted on NNs in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The first working deep learning algorithm was the group method of data handling, a method to train arbitrarily deep neural networks, published by Alexey Ivakhnenko and Valentin Lapa in the Soviet Union (1965).
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] They regarded it as a form of polynomial regression, generalizing Rosenblatt's perceptron.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] A 1971 paper described a deep network with eight layers trained by this method, training layer by layer via regression analysis.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Superfluous hidden units were pruned using a separate validation set.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The activation functions of the nodes were Kolmogorov-Gabor polynomials, the first deep networks with multiplicative units or "gates".
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The first deep learning multilayer perceptron (MLP) trained by stochastic gradient descent was published in 1967 by Shun'ichi Amari.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In computer experiments conducted by Amari's student S.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Saito, a five layer MLP with two modifiable layers learned internal representations to classify non-linearily separable pattern classes.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Subsequent developments in hardware and hyperparameter tuning made end-to-end stochastic gradient descent the dominant technique for reducing loss (error).
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1969, Kunihiko Fukushima introduced the ReLU (rectified linear unit) activation function.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] RelLU is the most common activation function.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Nevertheless, research stagnated in the United States after Minsky and Papert (1969), who emphasized that perceptrons were incapable of processing the exclusive-or circuit.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, this insight was irrelevant for the deep networks of Ivakhnenko (1965) and Amari (1967).
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1976, transfer learning was introduced.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Interest in neural networks revived during the 1980s because of the novel backpropagation algorithm, which allowed multi-layer neural networks to be trained efficiently by propagating error gradients backward (from output back to input) through network layers.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Backpropagation is an efficient application of the chain rule derived by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz in 1673 to networks of differentiable nodes.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The terminology "back-propagating errors" was introduced in 1962 by Rosenblatt, but he did not describe how to implement this.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Kelley developed a precursor of backpropagation in 1960 in the context of control theory.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1970, Seppo Linnainmaa published the modern form of backpropagation in his master's thesis (1970).
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Ostrovski et al. republished it in 1971.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Paul Werbos applied backpropagation to neural networks in 1982 (his 1974 PhD thesis, reprinted in a 1994 book, did not describe the algorithm).
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Rumelhart, et al., popularized backpropagation but did not cite the original work.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Deep learning architectures for convolutional neural networks (CNNs) with convolutional layers and downsampling layers and weight replication began with the neocognitron introduced by Kunihiko Fukushima in 1979.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Fukushima's CNN architecture also introduced max pooling, a popular downsampling procedure for CNNs.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] CNNs have become an essential tool for computer vision.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The time delay neural network (TDNN) was introduced in 1987 by Alex Waibel to apply CNNs to phoneme recognition.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] It used convolutions, weight sharing, and backpropagation.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1988, Wei Zhang applied a backpropagation-trained CNN to recognizing individual letters.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1989, Yann LeCun et al. created a CNN called LeNet for recognizing handwritten ZIP codes on mail.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1990, Wei Zhang implemented a CNN on optical computing hardware.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1991, a CNN was applied to medical image object segmentation and breast cancer detection in mammograms.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] LeNet-5 (1998), a 7-level CNN by Yann LeCun et al. that classifies hand-written digits, was applied by banks to recognize numbers on checks digitized in 32×32 pixel images.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] From 1988 onward, the use of neural networks transformed the field of protein structure prediction, in particular when the first cascading networks were trained on *profiles* (matrices) produced by multiple sequence alignments.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] One source of RNN was statistical mechanics.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1972, Shun'ichi Amari proposed to modify the weights of an Ising model by Hebbian learning rule as a model of associative memory, adding in learning.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] This was popularized as the Hopfield network by John Hopfield (1982).
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The word "recurrent" is used to describe loop-like structures in anatomy.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1901, Cajal observed "recurrent semicircles" in the cerebellar cortex.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Hebb considered "reverberating circuit" as an explanation for short-term memory.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The McCulloch and Pitts paper (1943) considered neural networks that contain cycles, and noted that the current activity of such networks can be affected by activity indefinitely far in the past.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1982 Crossbar Adaptive Array, a recurrent neural network with an array architecture (rather than a multilayer perceptron architecture), used direct recurrent connections from the output to the supervisor (teaching) inputs.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In addition to computing actions (decisions), it computed internal state evaluations (emotions) of consequence situations.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Eliminating the external supervisor, it introduced the self-learning method in neural networks.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In cognitive psychology, the *American Psychologist* journal in the early 1980s debated the relation between cognition and emotion.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Social psychologist Robert Zajonc in 1980 stated that emotion is computed first and is independent from cognition, while Richard Lazarus in 1982 stated that cognition is computed first and is inseparable from emotion.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] It was an example of a debate where an RNN contributed to an issue and also addressed cognitive psychology.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The Jordan network (1986) and the Elman network (1990) applied RNN to study cognitive psychology.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In the 1980s, backpropagation did not work well for deep RNNs.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1991, Jürgen Schmidhuber proposed the "neural sequence chunker" or "neural history compressor" which introduced self-supervised pre-training (the "P" in ChatGPT) and neural knowledge distillation.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1993, a neural history compressor system solved a "Very Deep Learning" task that required more than 1000 layers in an RNN unfolded in time.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1991, Sepp Hochreiter's diploma thesis identified and analyzed the vanishing gradient problem and proposed recurrent residual connections to solve it.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] He and Schmidhuber introduced long short-term memory (LSTM), which set accuracy records in multiple application domains.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] This was not the ultimate version of LSTM, which required the forget gate, and was introduced in 1999.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] It became the default choice for RNN architecture.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] During 1985–1995, inspired by statistical mechanics, several architectures and methods were developed by Terry Sejnowski, Peter Dayan, Geoffrey Hinton, and others, including the Boltzmann machine, restricted Boltzmann machine, Helmholtz machine, and the wake-sleep algorithm.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] These were designed for unsupervised learning of deep generative models.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Between 2009 and 2012, NNs began winning prizes in image recognition contests, approaching human performance on various tasks, initially in pattern recognition and handwriting recognition.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 2011, *DanNet,* a CNN by Dan Ciresan, Ueli Meier, Jonathan Masci, Luca Maria Gambardella, and Schmidhuber achieved for the first time superhuman performance in a visual pattern recognition contest, outperforming traditional methods by a factor of 3.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] They also showed how max-pooling CNNs on GPU improved performance.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In October 2012, AlexNet by Alex Krizhevsky, Ilya Sutskever, and Hinton won the large-scale ImageNet competition by a significant margin over shallow machine learning methods.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Further incremental improvements included the VGG-16 network by Karen Simonyan and Andrew Zisserman and Google's Inceptionv3.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 2012, Ng and Dean created a network that learned to recognize higher-level concepts, such as cats, from training only on unlabeled images.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Unsupervised pre-training and increased computing power from GPUs and distributed computing allowed the use of larger networks, particularly in image and visual recognition problems, which became known as "deep learning".
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Radial basis function and wavelet networks were introduced in 2013.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] These can be shown to offer best approximation properties and have been applied in nonlinear system identification and classification applications.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Generative adversarial networks (GANs) (Ian Goodfellow et al., 2014) became state of the art in generative modeling from 2014–2018.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] GAN was originally published in 1991 by Schmidhuber, who called it "artificial curiosity": two neural networks contest with each other in the form of a zero-sum game, where one network's gain is the other network's loss.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The first network is a generative model that models a probability distribution over output patterns.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The second network learns by gradient descent to predict the reactions of the environment to these patterns.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Excellent image quality was achieved by Nvidia's StyleGAN (2018) based on the Progressive GAN by Tero Karras et al.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Here, the GAN generator is grown from small to large scale in a pyramidal fashion.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Image generation by GAN reached popular success, and provoked discussions concerning deepfakes.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Diffusion models (2015) eclipsed GANs in generative modeling thereafter, with systems such as DALL·E 2 (2022) and Stable Diffusion (2022).
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 2014, the state of the art was training "[a] very deep neural network" with 20 to 30 layers.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Stacking too many layers led to a steep reduction in training accuracy, known as the "degradation" problem.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 2015, training very deep networks advanced with the highway network, published in May, and the residual neural network (ResNet) in December.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] ResNet behaves like an open-gated Highway Net.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] During the 2010s, the seq2seq model was developed, and attention mechanisms were added.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] This led to the modern transformer architecture in 2017 in "Attention Is All You Need".
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] It requires computation time that is quadratic in the size of the context window.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Schmidhuber's fast weight controller (1992) scales linearly and was later shown to be equivalent to the unnormalized linear transformer.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Transformers have increasingly become the model of choice for natural language processing.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Many modern large language models such as GPT, Gemini, Grok, DeepSeek, and Qwen use this architecture.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs began as an attempt to replicate the architecture of the brain in the digital realm.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs immediately showed promise for handling non-linear relationships, but encountered obstacles.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Models soon reoriented to applying mathematical insights to improve empirical results, at the expense of biological fidelity.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs are composed of digital neurons, conceptually derived from biological neurons.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Each neuron has one or more numerical inputs and produces a single numerical output.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] An input (e.g., an image) is typically parceled across the set of input neurons (each getting a piece of the image).
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Each neuron's inputs, weighted by the weights of the connections from each of those inputs are summed.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] A bias term is added to this sum.) The result is then passed through a nonlinear activation function to produce the neuron's output.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Small enough outputs may be zeroed out (ignored).
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs connect neurons to each other, using the output of some neurons as the input of others, akin to biological axon-synapse-dendrite connections.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The network forms a directed, weighted graph.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The weights apply to both the graph's the nodes and edges.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Nodes are arranged in layers, with the bottom layers directly addressing raw data, while the top layers reveal the final results.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Intermediate layers gradually increase the level of abstraction, so what began as for example, pixels in an image, gradually resolves into things such as object boundaries, and then into real-world objects such as letters and faces.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Single layer and unlayered networks are also used.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Multiple connection patterns have been used.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Traditionally, they are *fully connected*, with every neuron in one layer connecting to every neuron in the next layer.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, in convolutional neural networks, some layers are *convolutional,* meaning each neuron in one layer is connected to a subset of neurons in the previous layer, such as those representing one section of an image.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In most neural networks, the outputs of the neurons in one layer are connected only to neurons in the immediately following layer (directed acyclic graph), meaning information only flows forward from one layer to the next.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] These are known as feedforward networks.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In contrast, networks that allow connections between neurons in the same or previous layers are known as recurrent networks.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Training/learning involves adjusting the weights of the network to improve the accuracy of the result.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs typically require vast numbers of sample inputs (far more than biological brains) to achieve a given level of function.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] This is done by minimizing the observed errors among sample observations.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Training takes place before a network is deployed, and (unlike brains) does not continue thereafter.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Instead, the network may be retrained from scratch as more sample data becomes available.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Empirical risk minimization adjusts node and link weights to minimize the difference (empirical risk), between the predicted output and the known values in the training samples.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] A defined loss function measures the degree of error.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Backpropagation spreads the error (adjusts the weights) from the output nodes across the network to the input nodes.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The intent is to allow the network to process data that is not included in the training samples.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] As long as the value of the loss function (its cost) continues to decline, the network is continuing to improve.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The function typically produces a statistic whose value is only approximate.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] When the cost is low, the difference between the output (*e.g.* almost certainly a cat) and the correct answer (a cat) is small.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Most learning models can be viewed as a straightforward application of optimization theory and statistical estimation.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Learning typically ends when additional observations do not usefully reduce the cost.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The cost typically approaches, but does not reach, 0.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] If no feasible amount of sample data yields a low cost, training is labeled a failure.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] While it is possible to assess a loss function ad hoc, typically it must exhibit desirable properties such as convexity, differentiability, and robustness.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In a probabilistic model, the model's posterior probability can be used as an inverse cost (higher values are better).
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Backpropagation is a method used to adjust the connection weights to compensate for errors found during learning.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The error amount is essentially divided among the connections.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Technically, backpropagation calculates the gradient (the derivative) of the loss function associated with a given state with respect to the weights.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The weight updates can be done via stochastic gradient descent or other methods, such as *extreme learning machines*, "no-prop" networks, training without backtracking, "weightless" networks, and non-connectionist neural networks.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] A hyperparameter is a parameter defining any configurable part of the network and learning process whose value is set prior to training.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Examples of hyperparameters include learning rate, sample batch size, number of nodes and layers, etc .
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The performance of a neural network is strongly influenced by hyperparameter choices, and thus may be adjusted during training (typically between training runs), a process called hyperparameter tuning or hyperparameter optimization.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The learning rate defines the size of the corrective steps that the model takes to adjust for errors in each observation.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] A high learning rate shortens training time, but with lower ultimate accuracy, while a lower learning rate takes longer, but with the potential for greater accuracy.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Optimizations such as quickprop are primarily aimed at accelerating learning.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In order to avoid oscillations such as connection weights that cycle between high and low values, and to improve the rate of convergence, refinements use an adaptive learning rate that increases or decreases as appropriate.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The concept of momentum allows the balance between the gradient and the previous change to be weighted such that the weight adjustment depends to some degree on the previous change.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] A momentum close to 0 emphasizes the gradient, while a value close to 1 emphasizes the last change.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Machine learning has involved a variety of approaches to training models, including supervised learning, unsupervised learning, reinforcement learning, and self-supervised learning.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Supervised learning pairs inputs and desired outputs.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The learning task is to produce the desired output for each input.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In this case, the cost is related to eliminating incorrect outputs.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] A commonly used cost is the mean-squared error, which tries to minimize the average squared error between the network's output and the desired output.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Tasks suited for supervised learning include pattern recognition (classification) and regression (function approximation).
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Supervised learning is applicable to sequential data (e.g., for handwriting, speech and gesture recognition).
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] This can be thought of as learning with a "teacher", in the form of a function that provides continuous feedback.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In unsupervised learning, input data is given along with the cost function for the data $\textstyle x$ and the output, without an "answer sheet".
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The cost function is dependent on the task (the model domain) and reflects *a priori* assumptions (implicit model properties, its parameters and the observed variables).
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] For example, the model $\textstyle f(x)=a$ treats $\textstyle a$ is a constant and the cost $\textstyle C=E[(x-f(x))^{2}]$ .
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Minimizing this cost produces a value of $\textstyle a$ that is equal to the mean of the data.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The cost function can be much more complicated.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Its form depends on the application: for example, in compression it could be related to the mutual information between $\textstyle x$ and $\textstyle f(x)$ , whereas in statistical modeling, it could be related to the posterior probability (in both examples, those quantities are maximized).
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Unsupervised learning is typically applied to estimation problems; applications include clustering, the estimation of statistical distributions, compression, and filtering.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Self-supervised learning (SSL) is a paradigm in machine learning where a model is trained on a task using the data itself to generate supervisory signals, rather than relying on externally-provided labels.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In the context of neural networks, self-supervised learning aims to leverage inherent structures or relationships within the input data to create meaningful training signals.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] SSL tasks are designed so that solving them requires capturing essential features or relationships in the data.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The input data is typically augmented or transformed in a way that creates pairs of related samples, where one sample serves as the input, and the other is used to formulate the supervisory signal.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] This augmentation can involve introducing noise, cropping, rotation, or other transformations.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Self-supervised learning more closely imitates the way humans learn to classify objects.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] During SSL, the model learns in two steps.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] First, the task is solved based on an auxiliary or pretext classification task using pseudo-labels, which help to initialize the model parameters.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Next, the actual task is performed with supervised or unsupervised learning.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Self-supervised learning has produced promising results in recent years, and has found practical application in fields such as audio processing, and is being used by Facebook and others for speech recognition.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In applications such as playing video games, an actor takes a string of actions, receiving a generally unpredictable response from the environment (the game) after each one.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The goal is to win the game (get the highest score).
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In reinforcement learning, the aim is to weight the network to increase the score.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] After each action the game generates an observation and an instantaneous cost, according to its rules.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The rules and the long-term cost can only be estimated.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] At any juncture, the agent decides whether to explore new actions to uncover their costs or to exploit prior learning to proceed more quickly.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Formally, the environment is modeled as a Markov decision process (MDP) with states $\textstyle {s_{1},...,s_{n}}\in S$ and actions $\textstyle {a_{1},...,a_{m}}\in A$ .
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Taken together, the two define a Markov chain (MC).
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The aim is to discover the lowest-cost MC.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Self-learning was introduced in 1982 along with a *crossbar adaptive array* (CAA) NN that could teach itself.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] It is a system with only one input, situation s, and only one output, action (or behavior) a.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] It has neither external advice input nor external reinforcement from the environment.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The CAA computes, in a crossbar fashion, both decisions about actions and emotions (feelings) about encountered situations.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The system is driven by the interaction between cognition and emotion.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The backpropagated value (secondary reinforcement) is the emotion toward the consequence situation.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The CAA exists in two environments, its behavioral environment, and its genetic environment, from which it receives initial emotions (only once) about to be encountered situations in the behavioral environment.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Having received the genome vector (species vector) from the genetic environment, the CAA will learn a goal-seeking behavior, in the behavioral environment that contains both desirable and undesirable situations.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Neuroevolution can create NN topologies and weights using evolutionary computation.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] It is competitive with gradient descent approaches.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Neuroevolution may be less prone to get caught in "dead ends".
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Topological deep learning, introduced in 2017, integrates topology with deep neural networks to address high-order data.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Initially rooted in algebraic topology, TDL evolved into a versatile framework incorporating tools from mathematical disciplines such as differential topology and geometric topology.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In a Bayesian framework, a distribution over the set of allowed models is chosen to minimize cost.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Evolutionary methods, gene expression programming, simulated annealing, expectation–maximization, non-parametric methods and particle swarm optimization are other learning algorithms.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Convergent recursion is a learning algorithm for cerebellar model articulation controller (CMAC) neural networks.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Learning can be either stochastic or batch.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Stochastic learning creates a weight adjustment for each sample.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In batch learning, weights are adjusted based on a batch of inputs, accumulating errors over the batch.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Stochastic learning introduces "noise" into the process, using the local gradient calculated from one data point; this reduces the chance of the network getting stuck in local minima.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, batch learning typically yields a faster, more stable descent to a local minimum, since each update is performed in the direction of the batch's average error.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] A common compromise is to use "mini-batches", small batches with samples in each batch selected stochastically from the entire data set.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Types of neural networks (NN) include a family of techniques.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The simplest types have static components, including number of units, number of layers, unit weights and topology.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Some types allow/require learning to be "supervised" by the operator, while others operate independently.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Some types operate purely in hardware, while others are purely software and run on general purpose computers.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The choice of model depends on the data and the application.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Models that work well with textual data are typically not the best choice for image data, etc.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] An important element is which training/learning the model uses.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Neural architecture search (NAS) uses machine learning to automate NN design.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] NAS has yielded networks that compare well with hand-designed systems.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The basic algorithm is to propose a candidate model, evaluate it against a dataset, and use the results as feedback to teach the NAS network.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Efforts include AutoML and AutoKeras. scikit-learn library provides functions to help with building a deep network from scratch.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Hyperparameters are design choices (they are not learned).
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The multilayer perceptron is a universal function approximator, as proven by the universal approximation theorem.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, the proof does not specify the number of neurons required, the network topology, the weights or the learning parameters.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] A recurrent architecture with rational-valued weights (as opposed to full precision real number-valued weights) has the power of a universal Turing machine, using a finite number of neurons and linear connections.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Further, the use of irrational values for weights results in a machine with super-Turing power.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] A model's "capacity" property is its ability to model any given function.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] It is related to the amount of information that can be stored in the network and to the notion of complexity.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Information capacity and the VC dimension are two metrics.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The capacity of a network of standard neurons (not convolutional) can be derived by four rules that derive from considering a neuron as an electrical element.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The information capacity captures the functions that the network can model given any data as input.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The VC dimension uses the principles of measure theory and finds the maximum capacity under optimal circumstances, given input data in a specific form.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The VC Dimension for arbitrary inputs is half the information capacity of a perceptron.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The VC Dimension for arbitrary points is sometimes referred to as Memory Capacity.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Models may not consistently converge on a single solution, because the system may get stuck in a local minima.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Alternatively, the optimization method used might not guarantee to converge should it begin far from any local minima.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Thirdly, for sufficiently large data or parameters, some methods are impractically slow/expensive.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Training may also cross some saddle point that may then prevent access to the solution.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] When the width of a network approaches infinity, it is well described by its first order Taylor expansion throughout training, and so inherits the convergence behavior of affine models.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] When parameter numbers are small, NNs often fit target functions from low to high frequencies.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] This behavior is referred to as spectral bias, or the frequency principle.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] This phenomenon is the opposite of the behavior of some well-studied iterative numerical schemes such as the Jacobi method.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Deeper neural networks are more biased towards low frequency functions.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Applications that must generalize well to unseen examples, must avoid over-training.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] This arises in convoluted or over-specified systems when the network capacity is much larger than needed.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Cross-validation and similar techniques can check for over-training and select appropriate hyperparameters to minimize generalization error.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Supervised neural networks that use a mean squared error (MSE) cost function can use formal statistical methods to determine the confidence of the trained model.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] The MSE on a validation set can be used as an estimate for variance.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] This value can then be used to calculate the confidence interval of network output, assuming a normal distribution.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] A confidence analysis made this way is statistically valid as long as the output probability distribution stays the same and the network is not modified.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] By adopting a softmax activation function, a generalization of the logistic function, on the output layer of the neural network (or a softmax component in a component-based network) for categorical target variables, the outputs can be interpreted as posterior probabilities.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] This is useful in classification as it gives a certainty measure.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Neural networks support a broad range of applications in image processing, speech recognition, natural language processing, finance, and medicine.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Because of their ability to model and reproduce nonlinear processes, neural networks have found applications in many disciplines.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have been used to diagnose cancers and to distinguish highly invasive cancer cell lines from less invasive lines using only cell shape data.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have been used to accelerate reliability analysis of infrastructures subject to natural disasters and to predict settling in building foundations.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] They are used to mitigate flooding by modelling rainfall-runoff.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have been used for building black-box models in geoscience: hydrology, ocean modelling and coastal engineering, and geomorphology.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have been employed in cybersecurity, with the objective to discriminate between legitimate and malicious activities.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] For example, machine learning has been used for classifying Android malware, for identifying domains belonging to threat actors and for detecting URLs posing a security risk.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Research is underway on penetration testing, for detecting botnets, credit cards frauds, and network intrusions.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have been proposed as a tool to solve partial differential equations in physics and simulate the properties of many-body open quantum systems.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In brain research NNs have studied short-term behavior of individual neurons, the dynamics of neural circuitry arise from interactions between individual neurons and how behavior can arise from abstract neural modules that represent complete subsystems.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Studies considered long-and short-term plasticity of neural systems and their relation to learning and memory from the individual neuron to the system level.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs show promise in profiling a user's interests from photos and discovering new stable materials by efficiently predicting the total energy of crystals.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs are employed in computer vision tasks such as image classification, object and facial recognition, and image segmentation.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] They have been applied to automated surveillance medical imaging for diagnosis.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs are used for speaker identification, speech-to-text, and text-to-speech conversion.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have conquered large vocabulary continuous speech recognition, outperforming traditional techniques.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] These advancements have enabled the development of more accurate and efficient voice-activated systems, enhancing user interfaces in technology products.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In natural language processing, NNs are used for tasks such as text classification, sentiment analysis, machine translation, to answer free-form questions, act as chatbots, and to summarize and analyze texts.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] This has implications for automated customer service, content moderation, and language understanding technologies.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs are used to model dynamic systems for tasks such as system identification, control design, autonomous vehicles, and optimization.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Large financial institutions use AI to assist with their investment practices.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] BlackRock's AI engine, Aladdin, is used both within the company and by clients to help with investment decisions.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Its functions include the use of natural language processing to analyze text such as news, broker reports, and social media feeds.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] It then gauges the sentiment on the companies mentioned and assigns a score.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Banks such as UBS and Deutsche Bank use SQREEM (Sequential Quantum Reduction and Extraction Model) to mine data to develop consumer profiles and match them with wealth management products.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] They enhance diagnostic accuracy, especially by interpreting complex medical imaging for early disease detection, and by predicting patient outcomes for personalized treatment planning.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] In drug discovery, NNs speed up the identification of potential drug candidates and predict their efficacy and safety, significantly reducing development time and costs.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Additionally, their application in personalized medicine and healthcare data analysis allows tailored therapies and efficient patient care management.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Neural networks are widely applied in cybersecurity for anomaly detection, malware classification, and intrusion detection.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] By learning patterns of normal system or network behavior, NNs can identify deviations that indicate malicious activity.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Transformers are used for content creation across numerous industries.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] They can analyze samples and produce outputs that match the style of an artist or musician.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] For instance, DALL-E trained on 650 million pairs of images and texts and can create artworks based on user text.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Companies such as AIVA and Jukedeck have used transformers to create original music.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have been used to create personalized advertisements.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] Film production companies have used NNs to analyze the financial success of a film.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have found uses in video game creation.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p02] NNs require millions of training samples to become functional.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p02] As of 2026, training a commercial LLM (GPT, Grok, Gemini) typically required hundreds of thousands of computers, and cost 10s of millions of dollars.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p02] A central claim of NNs is that they embody new and powerful general principles for processing information.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p02] However, at root they use statistical long-developed methods.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p02] Neural networks require enormous computing resources for training.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p02] While the brain requires only 20 watts of power, training commercial transformers requires (2026) data centers with hundreds of megawatts.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p02] From 1991 to 2015, computing power, especially as delivered by GPGPUs (on GPUs), increased around a million-fold, enabling the use of the backpropagation algorithm.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p02] Neuromorphic engineering or a physical neural network constructed non-von-Neumann chips to directly implement neural networks in circuitry.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p02] For example, Alphabet introduced custom chips (Tensor Processing Unit).
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p02] The statistical properties of input data may change over time, a phenomenon known as concept drift or non-stationarity.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p02] Drift can reduce predictive accuracy and lead to unreliable or biased decisions if it is not detected and corrected.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p02] In practice, this means that the model's accuracy in deployment may differ substantially from levels observed during training.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p02] Neural networks are dependent on the quality of their training data; low quality data can lead the model to product poor results.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p02] Biased data produces biased results, requiring trainers to detect and correct them.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p02] For example, data that underrepresents some demographic groups may prevent cause errors, e.g., in facial recognition and law enforcement.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p02] In 2018, Amazon scrapped a recruiting tool because the model favored men over women for jobs in software engineering due to the larger number of male workers in the field.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p02] The system penalized resumes with the word "woman" or the name of a women's college.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p02] One corrective is to add synthetic data to offset the bias.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p02] NNs are "black box" systems that have complicated understanding of their decision-making processes.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p02] NNs are further vulnerable to adversarial examples ("poison"), that can cause incorrect predictions.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p02] These concerns have led to increased research in explainable artificial intelligence (XAI), robust machine learning, and hybrid AI approaches that combine neural learning with symbolic reasoning.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p02] Advocates of hybrid models also say that such a mixture can better capture the mechanisms of the human mind.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p02] Progress has included local vs. non-local learning and shallow vs. deep architectures.
[src:machine-learning/artificial-neural-network-p02] Analyzing human thought (a biological neural network) has also proven difficult.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] In machine learning, **attention** is a method that determines the importance of each component in a sequence relative to the other components in that sequence.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] In natural language processing, importance is represented by "soft" weights assigned to each word in a sentence.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] More generally, attention encodes vectors called token embeddings across a fixed-width sequence that can range from tens to millions of tokens in size.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] Unlike "hard" weights, which are computed during the backwards training pass, "soft" weights exist only in the forward pass and therefore change with every step of the input.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] Earlier designs implemented the attention mechanism in a serial recurrent neural network (RNN) language translation system, but a more recent design, namely the transformer, removed the slower sequential RNN and relied more heavily on the faster parallel attention scheme.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] Inspired by ideas about attention in humans, the attention mechanism was developed to address the weaknesses of using information from the hidden layers of recurrent neural networks.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] Recurrent neural networks favor information contained in words at the end of a sentence and thus deemed more recent, thereby tending to attenuate the significance and associated predictive weight assigned to information earlier in the sentence.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] Attention allows a token equal access to any part of a sentence directly, rather than only through the previous state.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] Additional surveys of the attention mechanism in deep learning are provided by Niu et al. and Soydaner.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] The major breakthrough came with self-attention, where each element in the input sequence attends to all others, enabling the model to capture global dependencies.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] This idea was central to the Transformer architecture, which replaced recurrence with attention mechanisms.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] As a result, Transformers became the foundation for models like BERT, T5 and generative pre-trained transformers (GPT).
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] The modern era of machine attention was revitalized by grafting an attention mechanism (Fig 1. orange) to an Encoder-Decoder.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] Figure 2 shows the internal step-by-step operation of the attention block (A) in Fig 1.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] The diagram shows the attention forward pass calculating correlations of the word "that" with other words in "See that girl run." Given the right weights from training, the network should be able to identify "girl" as a highly correlated word.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] In translating between languages, alignment is the process of matching words from the source sentence to words of the translated sentence.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] Networks that perform verbatim translation without regard to word order would show the highest scores along the (dominant) diagonal of the matrix.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] The off-diagonal dominance shows that the attention mechanism is more nuanced.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] Consider an example of translating *I love you* to French.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] On the first pass through the decoder, 94% of the attention weight is on the first English word *I*, so the network offers the word *je*.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] On the second pass of the decoder, 88% of the attention weight is on the third English word *you*, so it offers *t'*.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] On the last pass, 95% of the attention weight is on the second English word *love*, so it offers *aime*.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] In the *I love you* example, the second word *love* is aligned with the third word *aime*.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] Sometimes, alignment can be multiple-to-multiple.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] For example, the English phrase *look it up* corresponds to *cherchez-le*.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] For convolutional neural networks, attention mechanisms can be distinguished by the dimension on which they operate, namely: spatial attention, channel attention, or combinations.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] These variants recombine the encoder-side inputs to redistribute those effects to each target output.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] Often, a correlation-style matrix of dot products provides the re-weighting coefficients.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] In the figures below, W is the matrix of context attention weights, similar to the formula in Overview section above.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] The size of the attention matrix is proportional to the square of the number of input tokens.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] Therefore, when the input is long, calculating the attention matrix requires a lot of GPU memory.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] Flash attention is an implementation that reduces the memory needs and increases efficiency without sacrificing accuracy.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] It achieves this by partitioning the attention computation into smaller blocks that fit into the GPU's faster on-chip memory, reducing the need to store large intermediate matrices and thus lowering memory usage while increasing computational efficiency.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] FlexAttention is an attention kernel developed by Meta that allows users to modify attention scores prior to softmax and dynamically chooses the optimal attention algorithm.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] Attention is widely used in natural language processing, computer vision, and speech recognition.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] In NLP, it improves context understanding in tasks like question answering and summarization.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] In vision, visual attention helps models focus on relevant image regions, enhancing object detection and image captioning.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] From the original paper on vision transformers (ViT), visualizing attention scores as a heat map (called saliency maps or attention maps) has become an important and routine way to inspect the decision making process of ViT models.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] One can compute the attention maps with respect to any attention head at any layer, while the deeper layers tend to show more semantically meaningful visualization.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] Attention rollout is a recursive algorithm to combine attention scores across all layers, by computing the dot product of successive attention maps.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] Because vision transformers are typically trained in a self-supervised manner, attention maps are generally not class-sensitive.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] When a classification head is attached to the ViT backbone, class-discriminative attention maps (CDAM) combines attention maps and gradients with respect to the class `[CLS]` token.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] Some class-sensitive interpretability methods originally developed for convolutional neural networks can be also applied to ViT, such as GradCAM, which back-propagates the gradients to the outputs of the final attention layer.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] Using attention as basis of explanation for the transformers in language and vision is not without debate.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] While some pioneering papers analyzed and framed attention scores as explanations, higher attention scores do not always correlate with greater impact on model performances.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] The matrix Q contains m queries, while matrices $K,V$ jointly contain an *unordered* set of n key-value pairs.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] Value vectors in matrix V are weighted using the weights resulting from the softmax operation, so that the rows of the m -by- $d_{v}$ output matrix are confined to the convex hull of the points in $\mathbb {R} ^{d_{v}}$ given by the rows of V .
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] To understand the permutation invariance and permutation equivariance properties of QKV attention, let $A\in \mathbb {R} ^{m\times m}$ and $B\in \mathbb {R} ^{n\times n}$ be permutation matrices; and $D\in \mathbb {R} ^{m\times n}$ an arbitrary matrix.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] These properties are inherited when applying linear transforms to the inputs and outputs of QKV attention blocks.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] For example, a simple self-attention function defined as: $X\mapsto {\text{Attention}}(XT_{q},XT_{k},XT_{v})$ is permutation equivariant with respect to re-ordering the rows of the input matrix X in a non-trivial way, because every row of the output is a function of all the rows of the input.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] Similar properties hold for *multi-head attention*, which is defined below.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] The softmax output, also in $\mathbb {R} ^{n\times n}$ is then *lower triangular*, with zeros in all elements above the diagonal.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] The masking ensures that for all $1\leq i<j\leq n$ , row i of the attention output is independent of row j of any of the three input matrices.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] The permutation invariance and equivariance properties of standard QKV attention do not hold for the masked variant.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] The permutation properties of (standard, unmasked) QKV attention apply here also.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] For permutation matrices, $A,B$ : ${\text{MultiHead}}(AQ,BK,BV)=A\,{\text{MultiHead}}(Q,K,V)$ from which we also see that multi-head self-attention: $X\mapsto {\text{MultiHead}}(XT_{q},XT_{k},XT_{v})$ is equivariant with respect to re-ordering of the rows of input matrix X .
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] ${\text{Attention}}(Q,K,V)={\text{softmax}}(QWK^{T})V$ where W is a learnable weight matrix.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] Self-attention is essentially the same as cross-attention, except that query, key, and value vectors all come from the same model.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] Both encoder and decoder can use self-attention, but with subtle differences.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] For encoder self-attention, we can start with a simple encoder without self-attention, such as an "embedding layer", which simply converts each input word into a vector by a fixed lookup table.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] This gives a sequence of hidden vectors $h_{0},h_{1},\dots$ .
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] This can be applied repeatedly, to obtain a multilayered encoder.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] This is the "encoder self-attention", sometimes called the "all-to-all attention", as the vector at every position can attend to every other.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] For decoder self-attention, all-to-all attention is inappropriate, because during the autoregressive decoding process, the decoder cannot attend to future outputs that has yet to be decoded.
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] This can be solved by forcing the attention weights $w_{ij}=0$ for all $i<j$ , called "causal masking".
[src:machine-learning/attention-machine-learning] This attention mechanism is the "causally masked self-attention".
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] In machine learning, **backpropagation** is a gradient computation method commonly used for training a neural network in computing parameter updates.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] It is an efficient application of the chain rule to neural networks.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Backpropagation efficiently computes the gradient of the loss with respect to the network weights for a single input–output example.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] It does this by propagating derivatives backward, one layer at a time, from the output layer to the input layer, thereby avoiding redundant chain-rule calculations.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Strictly speaking, the term *backpropagation* refers only to an algorithm for efficiently computing the gradient, not how the gradient is used, but the term is often used loosely to refer to the entire learning algorithm.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] This includes changing model parameters in the negative direction of the gradient, such as by stochastic gradient descent, or as an intermediate step in a more complicated optimizer, such as Adaptive Moment Estimation.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Backpropagation had multiple discoveries and partial discoveries, with a tangled history and terminology (see § History).
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Some other names for the technique include "reverse mode of automatic differentiation" or "reverse accumulation".
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Backpropagation computes the gradient in weight space of a feedforward neural network, with respect to a loss function.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] In the derivation of backpropagation, other intermediate quantities are used by introducing them as needed below.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Bias terms are not treated specially since they correspond to a weight with a fixed input of 1.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] For backpropagation the specific loss function and activation functions do not matter as long as they and their derivatives can be evaluated efficiently.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Traditional activation functions include sigmoid, tanh, ReLU, Swish, Mish, and many others.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] For a training set there will be a set of input–output pairs, $\left\{(x_{i},y_{i})\right\}$ .
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Note the distinction: during model evaluation the weights are fixed while the inputs vary (and the target output may be unknown), and the network ends with the output layer (it does not include the loss function).
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] During model training the input–output pair is fixed while the weights vary, and the network ends with the loss function.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Backpropagation computes the gradient for a *fixed* input–output pair $(x_{i},y_{i})$ , where the weights $w_{jk}^{l}$ can vary.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Each individual component of the gradient, $\partial C/\partial w_{jk}^{l},$ can be computed by the chain rule; but doing this separately for each weight is inefficient.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Backpropagation efficiently computes the gradient by avoiding duplicate calculations and not computing unnecessary intermediate values, by computing the gradient of each layer – specifically the gradient of the weighted *input* of each layer, denoted by $\delta ^{l}$ – from back to front.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] First, it avoids duplication because when computing the gradient at layer l , it is unnecessary to recompute all derivatives on later layers $l+1,l+2,\ldots$ each time.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Backpropagation can be expressed for simple feedforward networks in terms of matrix multiplication, or more generally in terms of the adjoint graph.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] To compute this, one starts with the input x and works forward; denote the weighted input of each hidden layer as $z^{l}$ and the output of hidden layer l as the activation $a^{l}$ .
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] For backpropagation, the activation $a^{l}$ as well as the derivatives $(f^{l})'$ (evaluated at $z^{l}$ ) must be cached for use during the backwards pass.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Note that $\delta ^{l}$ is a vector, of length equal to the number of nodes in level l ; each component is interpreted as the "cost attributable to (the value of) that node".
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] The factor of $a^{l-1}$ is because the weights $W^{l}$ between level $l-1$ and l affect level l proportionally to the inputs (activations): the inputs are fixed, the weights vary.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] The gradients of the weights can thus be computed using a few matrix multiplications for each level; this is backpropagation.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Multiplying starting from $\nabla _{a^{L}}C$ – propagating the error *backwards* – means that each step simply multiplies a vector ( $\delta ^{l}$ ) by the matrices of weights $(W^{l})^{T}$ and derivatives of activations $(f^{l-1})'$ .
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] By contrast, multiplying forwards, starting from the changes at an earlier layer, means that each multiplication multiplies a *matrix* by a *matrix*.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] For more general graphs, and other advanced variations, backpropagation can be understood in terms of automatic differentiation, where backpropagation is a special case of reverse accumulation (or "reverse mode").
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] The goal of any supervised learning algorithm is to find a function that best maps a set of inputs to their correct output.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] The motivation for backpropagation is to train a multi-layered neural network such that it can learn the appropriate internal representations to allow it to learn any arbitrary mapping of input to output.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] To understand the mathematical derivation of the backpropagation algorithm, it helps to first develop some intuition about the relationship between the actual output of a neuron and the correct output for a particular training example.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Consider a simple neural network with two input units, one output unit and no hidden units, and in which each neuron uses a linear output (unlike most work on neural networks, in which mapping from inputs to outputs is non-linear) that is the weighted sum of its input.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Initially, before training, the weights will be set randomly.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Then the neuron learns from training examples, which in this case consist of a set of tuples $(x_{1},x_{2},t)$ where $x_{1}$ and $x_{2}$ are the inputs to the network and t is the correct output (the output the network should produce given those inputs, when it has been trained).
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] The initial network, given $x_{1}$ and $x_{2}$ , will compute an output y that likely differs from t (given random weights).
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] A loss function $L(t,y)$ is used for measuring the discrepancy between the target output t and the computed output y.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] For regression analysis problems the squared error can be used as a loss function, for classification the categorical cross-entropy can be used.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Consider the network on a single training case: $(1,1,0)$ .
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Thus, the input $x_{1}$ and $x_{2}$ are 1 and 1 respectively and the correct output, t is 0.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Now if the relation is plotted between the network's output y on the horizontal axis and the error E on the vertical axis, the result is a parabola.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] The minimum of the parabola corresponds to the output y which minimizes the error E.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] For a single training case, the minimum also touches the horizontal axis, which means the error will be zero and the network can produce an output y that exactly matches the target output t.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Therefore, the problem of mapping inputs to outputs can be reduced to an optimization problem of finding a function that will produce the minimal error.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] where $w_{1}$ and $w_{2}$ are the weights on the connection from the input units to the output unit.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Therefore, the error also depends on the incoming weights to the neuron, which is ultimately what needs to be changed in the network to enable learning.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Then, the loss function E takes the form of a parabolic cylinder with its base directed along $w_{1}=-w_{2}$ .
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Since all sets of weights that satisfy $w_{1}=-w_{2}$ minimize the loss function, in this case additional constraints are required to converge to a unique solution.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Additional constraints could either be generated by setting specific conditions to the weights, or by injecting additional training data.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] One commonly used algorithm to find the set of weights that minimizes the error is gradient descent.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] By backpropagation, the steepest descent direction is calculated of the loss function versus the present synaptic weights.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Then, the weights can be modified along the steepest descent direction, and the error is minimized in an efficient way.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] The gradient descent method involves calculating the derivative of the loss function with respect to the weights of the network.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] This is normally done using backpropagation.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] is the actual output of the output neuron.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] In this section, the order of the weight indexes are reversed relative to the prior section: $w_{ij}$ is weight from the i th to the j th unit.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] where the activation function $\varphi$ is non-linear and differentiable over the activation region (the ReLU is not differentiable at one point).
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] The input ${\text{net}}_{j}$ to a neuron is the weighted sum of outputs $o_{k}$ of previous neurons.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] If the neuron is in the first layer after the input layer, the $o_{k}$ of the input layer are simply the inputs $x_{k}$ to the network.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] The number of input units to the neuron is n .
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] The variable $w_{kj}$ denotes the weight between neuron k of the previous layer and neuron j of the current layer.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] If the neuron is in the first layer after the input layer, $o_{i}$ is just $x_{i}$ .
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] This is the reason why backpropagation requires that the activation function be differentiable.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] However, if j is in an arbitrary inner layer of the network, finding the derivative E with respect to $o_{j}$ is less obvious.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] To update the weight $w_{ij}$ using gradient descent, one must choose a learning rate, $\eta >0$ .
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] The change in weight needs to reflect the impact on E of an increase or decrease in $w_{ij}$ .
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] If ${\frac {\partial E}{\partial w_{ij}}}>0$ , an increase in $w_{ij}$ increases E ; conversely, if ${\frac {\partial E}{\partial w_{ij}}}<0$ , an increase in $w_{ij}$ decreases E .
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] The new $\Delta w_{ij}$ is added to the old weight, and the product of the learning rate and the gradient, multiplied by $-1$ guarantees that $w_{ij}$ changes in a way that always decreases E .
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Using a Hessian matrix of second-order derivatives of the error function, the Levenberg–Marquardt algorithm often converges faster than first-order gradient descent, especially when the topology of the error function is complicated.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] It may also find solutions in smaller node counts for which other methods might not converge.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] The Hessian can be approximated by the Fisher information matrix.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] As an example, consider a simple feedforward network.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Arbitrary-order derivatives in arbitrary computational graphs can be computed with backpropagation, but with more complex expressions for higher orders.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] The loss function is a function that maps values of one or more variables onto a real number intuitively representing some "cost" associated with those values.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] For backpropagation, the loss function calculates the difference between the network output and its expected output, after a training example has propagated through the network.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] The mathematical expression of the loss function must fulfill two conditions in order for it to be possibly used in backpropagation.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] The first is that it can be written as an average ${\textstyle E={\frac {1}{n}}\sum _{x}E_{x}}$ over error functions ${\textstyle E_{x}}$ , for ${\textstyle n}$ individual training examples, ${\textstyle x}$ .
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] The reason for this assumption is that the backpropagation algorithm calculates the gradient of the error function for a single training example, which needs to be generalized to the overall error function.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] The second assumption is that it can be written as a function of the outputs from the neural network.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Select an error function $E(y,y')$ measuring the difference between two outputs.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Backpropagation had been derived repeatedly, as it is essentially an efficient application of the chain rule (first written down by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz in 1676) to neural networks.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] The terminology "back-propagating error correction" was introduced in 1962 by Frank Rosenblatt, but he did not know how to implement this.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] In any case, he only studied neurons whose outputs were discrete levels, which only had zero derivatives, making backpropagation impossible.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Precursors to backpropagation appeared in optimal control theory since 1950s.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Yann LeCun et al credits 1950s work by Pontryagin and others in optimal control theory, especially the adjoint state method, for being a continuous-time version of backpropagation.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Hecht-Nielsen credits the Robbins–Monro algorithm (1951) and Arthur Bryson and Yu-Chi Ho's *Applied Optimal Control* (1969) as presages of backpropagation.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] In 1962, Stuart Dreyfus published a simpler derivation based only on the chain rule.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] In 1973, he adapted parameters of controllers in proportion to error gradients.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Unlike modern backpropagation, these precursors used standard Jacobian matrix calculations from one stage to the previous one, neither addressing direct links across several stages nor potential additional efficiency gains due to network sparsity.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] The ADALINE (1960) learning algorithm was gradient descent with a squared error loss for a single layer.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] The first multilayer perceptron (MLP) with more than one layer trained by stochastic gradient descent was published in 1967 by Shun'ichi Amari.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] The MLP had 5 layers, with 2 learnable layers, and it learned to classify patterns not linearly separable.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Modern backpropagation was first published by Seppo Linnainmaa as "reverse mode of automatic differentiation" (1970) for discrete connected networks of nested differentiable functions.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] In 1982, Paul Werbos applied backpropagation to MLPs in the way that has become standard.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Werbos described how he developed backpropagation in an interview.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] In 1971, during his PhD work, he developed backpropagation to mathematicize Freud's "flow of psychic energy".
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] He faced repeated difficulty in publishing the work, only managing in 1981.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] He also claimed that "the first practical application of back-propagation was for estimating a dynamic model to predict nationalism and social communications in 1974" by him.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Rumelhart independently developed backpropagation and taught the algorithm to others in his research circle.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] He did not cite previous work as he was unaware of them.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] He published the algorithm first in a 1985 paper, then in a 1986 *Nature* paper an experimental analysis of the technique.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] These papers became highly cited, contributed to the popularization of backpropagation, and coincided with the resurging research interest in neural networks during the 1980s.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] In 1985, the method was also described by David Parker.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Yann LeCun proposed an alternative form of backpropagation for neural networks in his PhD thesis in 1987.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Gradient descent took a considerable amount of time to reach acceptance.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Some early objections were: there were no guarantees that gradient descent could reach a global minimum, only local minimum; neurons were "known" by physiologists as making discrete signals (0/1), not continuous ones, and with discrete signals, there is no gradient to take.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] See the interview with Geoffrey Hinton, who was awarded the 2024 Nobel Prize in Physics for his contributions to the field.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Contributing to the acceptance were several applications in training neural networks via backpropagation, sometimes achieving popularity outside the research circles.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] In 1987, NETtalk learned to convert English text into pronunciation.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Sejnowski tried training it with both backpropagation and Boltzmann machine, but found the backpropagation significantly faster, so he used it for the final NETtalk.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] The NETtalk program became a popular success, appearing on the *Today* show.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Pomerleau published ALVINN, a neural network trained to drive autonomously using backpropagation.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] The LeNet was published in 1989 to recognize handwritten zip codes.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] In 1992, TD-Gammon achieved top human level play in backgammon.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] It was a reinforcement learning agent with a neural network with two layers, trained by backpropagation.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] In 1993, Eric Wan won an international pattern recognition contest through backpropagation.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] During the 2000s it fell out of favour, but returned in the 2010s, benefiting from cheap, powerful GPU-based computing systems.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] Error backpropagation has been suggested to explain human brain event-related potential (ERP) components like the N400 and P600.
[src:machine-learning/backpropagation] In 2023, a backpropagation algorithm was implemented on a photonic processor by a team at Stanford University.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A **convolutional neural network** (**CNN**) is a type of feedforward neural network that learns features via filter (or kernel) optimization.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This type of deep learning network has been applied to process and make predictions from many different types of data including text, images and audio.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs are the de-facto standard in deep learning-based approaches to computer vision and image processing, and have only recently been replaced—in some cases—by newer architectures such as the transformer.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Vanishing gradients and exploding gradients, seen during backpropagation in earlier neural networks, are prevented by the regularization that comes from using shared weights over fewer connections.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, for *each* neuron in the fully-connected layer, 10,000 weights would be required for processing an image sized 100 × 100 pixels.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, applying cascaded *convolution* (or cross-correlation) kernels, only 25 weights for each convolutional layer are required to process 5x5-sized tiles.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Higher-layer features are extracted from wider context windows, compared to lower-layer features.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs are also known as **shift invariant** or **space invariant artificial neural networks**, based on the shared-weight architecture of the convolution kernels or filters that slide along input features and provide translation-equivariant responses known as feature maps.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Counter-intuitively, most convolutional neural networks are not invariant to translation, due to the downsampling operation they apply to the input.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Feedforward neural networks are usually fully connected networks, that is, each neuron in one layer is connected to all neurons in the next layer.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "full connectivity" of these networks makes them prone to overfitting data.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks were inspired by biological processes in that the connectivity pattern between neurons resembles the organization of the animal visual cortex.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Individual cortical neurons respond to stimuli only in a restricted region of the visual field known as the receptive field.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The receptive fields of different neurons partially overlap such that they cover the entire visual field.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use relatively little pre-processing compared to other image classification algorithms.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This means that the network learns to optimize the filters (or kernels) through automated learning, whereas in traditional algorithms these filters are hand-engineered.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This simplifies and automates the process, enhancing efficiency and scalability overcoming human-intervention bottlenecks.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A convolutional neural network consists of an input layer, hidden layers and an output layer.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a convolutional neural network, the hidden layers include one or more layers that perform convolutions.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Typically this includes a layer that performs a dot product of the convolution kernel with the layer's input matrix.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This product is usually the Frobenius inner product, and its activation function is commonly ReLU.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As the convolution kernel slides along the input matrix for the layer, the convolution operation generates a feature map, which in turn contributes to the input of the next layer.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is followed by other layers such as pooling layers, fully connected layers, and normalization layers.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Here it should be noted how close a convolutional neural network is to a matched filter.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (number of inputs) × (feature map height) × (feature map width) × (feature map channels).
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional layers convolve the input and pass its result to the next layer.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is similar to the response of a neuron in the visual cortex to a specific stimulus.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each convolutional neuron processes data only for its receptive field.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Although fully connected feedforward neural networks can be used to learn features and classify data, this architecture is generally impractical for larger inputs (e.g., high-resolution images), which would require massive numbers of neurons because each pixel is a relevant input feature.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A fully connected layer for an image of size 100 × 100 has 10,000 weights for *each* neuron in the second layer.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolution reduces the number of free parameters, allowing the network to be deeper.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, using a 5 × 5 tiling region, each with the same shared weights, requires only 25 neurons.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Using shared weights means there are many fewer parameters, which helps avoid the vanishing gradients and exploding gradients problems seen during backpropagation in earlier neural networks.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To speed processing, standard convolutional layers can be replaced by depthwise separable convolutional layers, which are based on a depthwise convolution followed by a pointwise convolution.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The *depthwise convolution* is a spatial convolution applied independently over each channel of the input tensor, while the *pointwise convolution* is a standard convolution restricted to the use of $1\times 1$ kernels.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks may include local and/or global pooling layers along with traditional convolutional layers.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling layers reduce the dimensions of data by combining the outputs of neuron clusters at one layer into a single neuron in the next layer.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Local pooling combines small clusters, tiling sizes such as 2 × 2 are commonly used.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Global pooling acts on all the neurons of the feature map.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] There are two common types of pooling in popular use: max and average.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] *Max pooling* uses the maximum value of each local cluster of neurons in the feature map, while *average pooling* takes the average value.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Fully connected layers connect every neuron in one layer to every neuron in another layer.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is the same as a traditional multilayer perceptron neural network (MLP).
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each neuron in the fully connected layer receives input from all the neurons in the previous layer.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] These inputs are weighted and summed with the corresponding biases, and then passed through an activation function to perform a nonlinear transformation, generating the output.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The flattened matrix goes through a fully connected layer to classify the images.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In neural networks, each neuron receives input from some number of locations in the previous layer.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a convolutional layer, each neuron receives input from only a restricted area of the previous layer called the neuron's *receptive field*.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Whereas, in a fully connected layer, the receptive field is the *entire previous layer*.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, in each convolutional layer, each neuron takes input from a larger area in the input than previous layers.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is due to applying the convolution over and over, which takes the value of a pixel into account, as well as its surrounding pixels.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] When using dilated layers, the number of pixels in the receptive field remains constant, but the field is more sparsely populated as its dimensions grow when combining the effect of several layers.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To manipulate the receptive field size as desired, there are some alternatives to the standard convolutional layer.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, atrous or dilated convolution expands the receptive field size without increasing the number of parameters by interleaving visible and blind regions.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Moreover, a single dilated convolutional layer can comprise filters with multiple dilation ratios, thus having a variable receptive field size.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each neuron in a neural network computes an output value by applying a specific function to the input values received from the receptive field in the previous layer.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The function that is applied to the input values is determined by a vector of weights and a bias (typically real numbers).
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Learning consists of iteratively adjusting these biases and weights.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The vectors of weights and biases are called *filters* and represent particular features of the input (e.g., a particular shape).
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A distinguishing feature of CNNs is that many neurons can share the same filter.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This reduces the memory footprint because a single bias and a single vector of weights are used across all receptive fields that share that filter, as opposed to each receptive field having its own bias and vector weighting.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A deconvolutional neural network is essentially the reverse of a CNN.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It consists of deconvolutional layers and unpooling layers.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A deconvolutional layer is the transpose of a convolutional layer.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Specifically, a convolutional layer can be written as a multiplication with a matrix, and a deconvolutional layer is multiplication with the transpose of that matrix.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The max-unpooling layer is the simplest, as it simply copies each entry multiple times.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a 2-by-2 max-unpooling layer is $[x]\mapsto {\begin{bmatrix}x&x\\x&x\end{bmatrix}}$ .
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Deconvolution layers are used in image generators.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] By default, it creates periodic checkerboard artifact, which can be fixed by upscale-then-convolve.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNN are often compared to the way the brain achieves vision processing in living organisms.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Work by Hubel and Wiesel in the 1950s and 1960s showed that cat visual cortices contain neurons that individually respond to small regions of the visual field.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Provided the eyes are not moving, the region of visual space within which visual stimuli affect the firing of a single neuron is known as its receptive field.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Neighboring cells have similar and overlapping receptive fields.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Receptive field size and location varies systematically across the cortex to form a complete map of visual space.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The cortex in each hemisphere represents the contralateral visual field.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Hubel and Wiesel also proposed a cascading model of these two types of cells for use in pattern recognition tasks.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the same paper, Fukushima also introduced the ReLU (rectified linear unit) activation function.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "neocognitron" was introduced by Fukushima in 1980.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Several supervised and unsupervised learning algorithms have been proposed over the decades to train the weights of a neocognitron.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Today, however, the CNN architecture is usually trained through backpropagation.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Fukushima's ReLU activation function was not used in his neocognitron since all the weights were nonnegative; lateral inhibition was used instead.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The rectifier has become a very popular activation function for CNNs and deep neural networks in general.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The term "convolution" first appears in neural networks in a paper by Toshiteru Homma, Les Atlas, and Robert Marks II at the first Conference on Neural Information Processing Systems in 1987.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their paper replaced multiplication with convolution in time, inherently providing shift invariance, motivated by and connecting more directly to the signal-processing concept of a filter, and demonstrated it on a speech recognition task.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They also pointed out that as a data-trainable system, convolution is essentially equivalent to correlation since reversal of the weights does not affect the final learned function ("For convenience, we denote * as correlation instead of convolution.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that convolving a(t) with b(t) is equivalent to correlating a(-t) with b(t).").
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Modern CNN implementations typically do correlation and call it convolution, for convenience, as they did here.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The time delay neural network (TDNN) was introduced in 1987 by Alex Waibel et al. for phoneme recognition and was an early convolutional network exhibiting shift-invariance.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A TDNN is a 1-D convolutional neural net where the convolution is performed along the time axis of the data.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is the first CNN utilizing weight sharing in combination with a training by gradient descent, using backpropagation.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, while also using a pyramidal structure as in the neocognitron, it performed a global optimization of the weights instead of a local one.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] TDNNs are convolutional networks that share weights along the temporal dimension.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They allow speech signals to be processed time-invariantly.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 1990 Hampshire and Waibel introduced a variant that performs a two-dimensional convolution.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since these TDNNs operated on spectrograms, the resulting phoneme recognition system was invariant to both time and frequency shifts, as with images processed by a neocognitron.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] TDNNs improved the performance of far-distance speech recognition.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1989) designed a 2-D CNN system to recognize hand-written ZIP Code numbers.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, the lack of an efficient training method to determine the kernel coefficients of the involved convolutions meant that all the coefficients had to be laboriously hand-designed.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Following the advances in the training of 1-D CNNs by Waibel et al.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1989) used back-propagation to learn the convolution kernel coefficients directly from images of hand-written numbers.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Learning was thus fully automatic, performed better than manual coefficient design, and was suited to a broader range of image recognition problems and image types.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1988) used back-propagation to train the convolution kernels of a CNN for alphabets recognition.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model was called shift-invariant pattern recognition neural network before the name CNN was coined later in the early 1990s.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Wei Zhang et al. also applied the same CNN without the last fully connected layer for medical image object segmentation (1991) and breast cancer detection in mammograms (1994).
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This approach became a foundation of modern computer vision.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 1990 Yamaguchi et al. introduced the concept of max pooling, a fixed filtering operation that calculates and propagates the maximum value of a given region.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They did so by combining TDNNs with max pooling to realize a speaker-independent isolated word recognition system.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In their system they used several TDNNs per word, one for each syllable.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The results of each TDNN over the input signal were combined using max pooling and the outputs of the pooling layers were then passed on to networks performing the actual word classification.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a variant of the neocognitron called the *cresceptron*, instead of using Fukushima's spatial averaging with inhibition and saturation, J.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Weng et al. in 1993 used max pooling, where a downsampling unit computes the maximum of the activations of the units in its patch, introducing this method into the vision field.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Max pooling is often used in modern CNNs.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] LeNet-5, a pioneering 7-level convolutional network by LeCun et al. in 1995, classifies hand-written numbers on checks digitized in 32×32 pixel images.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The ability to process higher-resolution images requires larger and more layers of convolutional neural networks, so this technique is constrained by the availability of computing resources.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was superior than other commercial courtesy amount reading systems (as of 1995).
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The system was integrated in NCR's check reading systems, and fielded in several American banks since June 1996, reading millions of checks per day.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A shift-invariant neural network was proposed by Wei Zhang et al. for image character recognition in 1988.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is a modified Neocognitron by keeping only the convolutional interconnections between the image feature layers and the last fully connected layer.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model was trained with back-propagation.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The training algorithm was further improved in 1991 to improve its generalization ability.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model architecture was modified by removing the last fully connected layer and applied for medical image segmentation (1991) and automatic detection of breast cancer in mammograms (1994).
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A different convolution-based design was proposed in 1988 for application to decomposition of one-dimensional electromyography convolved signals via de-convolution.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This design was modified in 1989 to other de-convolution-based designs.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Although CNNs were invented in the 1980s, their breakthrough in the 2000s required fast implementations on graphics processing units (GPUs).
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Jung that standard neural networks can be greatly accelerated on GPUs.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their implementation was 20 times faster than an equivalent implementation on CPU.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2005, another paper also emphasised the value of GPGPU for machine learning.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The first GPU-implementation of a CNN was described in 2006 by K.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their implementation was 4 times faster than an equivalent implementation on CPU.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the same period, GPUs were also used for unsupervised training of deep belief networks.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2010, Dan Ciresan et al. at IDSIA trained deep feedforward networks on GPUs.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, they extended this to CNNs, accelerating by 60 compared to training CPU.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, the network won an image recognition contest where they achieved superhuman performance for the first time.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Then they won more competitions and achieved state of the art on several benchmarks.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Subsequently, AlexNet, a similar GPU-based CNN by Alex Krizhevsky et al. won the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge 2012.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was an early catalytic event for the AI boom.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Compared to the training of CNNs using GPUs, not much attention was given to CPU.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (Viebke et al 2019) parallelizes CNN by thread- and SIMD-level parallelism that is available on the Intel Xeon Phi.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the past, traditional multilayer perceptron (MLP) models were used for image recognition.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, the full connectivity between nodes caused the curse of dimensionality, and was computationally intractable with higher-resolution images.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A 1000×1000-pixel image with RGB color channels has 3 million weights per fully-connected neuron, which is too high to feasibly process efficiently at scale.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, in CIFAR-10, images are only of size 32×32×3 (32 wide, 32 high, 3 color channels), so a single fully connected neuron in the first hidden layer of a regular neural network would have 32*32*3 = 3,072 weights.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Also, such network architecture does not take into account the spatial structure of data, treating input pixels which are far apart in the same way as pixels that are close together.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This ignores locality of reference in data with a grid-topology (such as images), both computationally and semantically.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, full connectivity of neurons is wasteful for purposes such as image recognition that are dominated by spatially local input patterns.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional neural networks are variants of multilayer perceptrons, designed to emulate the behavior of a visual cortex.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] These models mitigate the challenges posed by the MLP architecture by exploiting the strong spatially local correlation present in natural images.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Together, these properties allow CNNs to achieve better generalization on vision problems.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Weight sharing dramatically reduces the number of free parameters learned, thus lowering the memory requirements for running the network and allowing the training of larger, more powerful networks.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A CNN architecture is formed by a stack of distinct layers that transform the input volume into an output volume (e.g. holding the class scores) through a differentiable function.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A few distinct types of layers are commonly used.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The convolutional layer is the core building block of a CNN.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The layer's parameters consist of a set of learnable filters (or kernels), which have a small receptive field, but extend through the full depth of the input volume.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] During the forward pass, each filter is convolved across the width and height of the input volume, computing the dot product between the filter entries and the input, producing a 2-dimensional activation map of that filter.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As a result, the network learns filters that activate when it detects some specific type of feature at some spatial position in the input.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Stacking the activation maps for all filters along the depth dimension forms the full output volume of the convolution layer.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Every entry in the output volume can thus also be interpreted as an output of a neuron that looks at a small region in the input.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each entry in an activation map use the same set of parameters that define the filter.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Self-supervised learning has been adapted for use in convolutional layers by using sparse patches with a high-mask ratio and a global response normalization layer.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] When dealing with high-dimensional inputs such as images, it is impractical to connect neurons to all neurons in the previous volume because such a network architecture does not take the spatial structure of the data into account.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks exploit spatially local correlation by enforcing a sparse local connectivity pattern between neurons of adjacent layers: each neuron is connected to only a small region of the input volume.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The extent of this connectivity is a hyperparameter called the receptive field of the neuron.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The connections are local in space (along width and height), but always extend along the entire depth of the input volume.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Such an architecture ensures that the learned filters produce the strongest response to a spatially local input pattern.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The spatial size of the output volume is a function of the input volume size W , the kernel field size K of the convolutional layer neurons, the stride S , and the amount of zero padding P on the border.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] If this number is not an integer, then the strides are incorrect and the neurons cannot be tiled to fit across the input volume in a symmetric way.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In general, setting zero padding to be ${\textstyle P=(K-1)/2}$ when the stride is $S=1$ ensures that the input volume and output volume will have the same size spatially.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, it is not always completely necessary to use all of the neurons of the previous layer.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a neural network designer may decide to use just a portion of padding.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A parameter sharing scheme is used in convolutional layers to control the number of free parameters.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It relies on the assumption that if a patch feature is useful to compute at some spatial position, then it should also be useful to compute at other positions.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Denoting a single 2-dimensional slice of depth as a *depth slice*, the neurons in each depth slice are constrained to use the same weights and bias.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since all neurons in a single depth slice share the same parameters, the forward pass in each depth slice of the convolutional layer can be computed as a convolution of the neuron's weights with the input volume.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Therefore, it is common to refer to the sets of weights as a filter (or a kernel), which is convolved with the input.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The result of this convolution is an activation map, and the set of activation maps for each different filter are stacked together along the depth dimension to produce the output volume.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Parameter sharing contributes to the translation invariance of the CNN architecture.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Sometimes, the parameter sharing assumption may not make sense.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is especially the case when the input images to a CNN have some specific centered structure; for which we expect completely different features to be learned on different spatial locations.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One practical example is when the inputs are faces that have been centered in the image: we might expect different eye-specific or hair-specific features to be learned in different parts of the image.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In that case it is common to relax the parameter sharing scheme, and instead simply call the layer a "locally connected layer".
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In this layer, the convolutional kernels' parameters are not shared.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Instead, the network learns independent weights and biases for each spatial location.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This allows each location to have its own feature-learning ability, making it better suited to handle images with distinct central structures or irregular features.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another important concept of CNNs is pooling, which is used as a form of non-linear down-sampling.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling provides downsampling because it reduces the spatial dimensions (height and width) of the input feature maps while retaining the most important information.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] There are several non-linear functions to implement pooling, where *max pooling* and *average pooling* are the most common.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling aggregates information from small regions of the input creating partitions of the input feature map, typically using a fixed-size window (like 2x2) and applying a stride (often 2) to move the window across the input.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that without using a stride greater than 1, pooling would not perform downsampling, as it would simply move the pooling window across the input one step at a time, without reducing the size of the feature map.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, the stride is what actually causes the downsampling by determining how much the pooling window moves over the input.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Intuitively, the exact location of a feature is less important than its rough location relative to other features.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is the idea behind the use of pooling in convolutional neural networks.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The pooling layer serves to progressively reduce the spatial size of the representation, to reduce the number of parameters, memory footprint and amount of computation in the network, and hence to also control overfitting.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is common to periodically insert a pooling layer between successive convolutional layers (each one typically followed by an activation function, such as a ReLU layer) in a CNN architecture.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] While pooling layers contribute to local translation invariance, they do not provide global translation invariance in a CNN, unless a form of global pooling is used.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The pooling layer commonly operates independently on every depth, or slice, of the input and resizes it spatially.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The depth dimension remains unchanged (this is true for other forms of pooling as well).
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In addition to max pooling, pooling units can use other functions, such as average pooling or ℓ2-norm pooling.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Average pooling was often used historically but has recently fallen out of favor compared to max pooling, which generally performs better in practice.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Due to the effects of fast spatial reduction of the size of the representation, there is a recent trend towards using smaller filters or discarding pooling layers altogether.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A channel max pooling (CMP) operation layer conducts the MP operation along the channel side among the corresponding positions of the consecutive feature maps for the purpose of redundant information elimination.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The CMP makes the significant features gather together within fewer channels, which is important for fine-grained image classification that needs more discriminating features.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Meanwhile, another advantage of the CMP operation is to make the channel number of feature maps smaller before it connects to the first fully connected (FC) layer.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Similar to the MP operation, we denote the input feature maps and output feature maps of a CMP layer as F ∈ R(C×M×N) and C ∈ R(c×M×N), respectively, where C and c are the channel numbers of the input and output feature maps, M and N are the widths and the height of the feature maps, respectively.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that the CMP operation only changes the channel number of the feature maps.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The width and the height of the feature maps are not changed, which is different from the MP operation.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU is the abbreviation of rectified linear unit.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was proposed by Alston Householder in 1941, and used in CNN by Kunihiko Fukushima in 1969.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU applies the non-saturating activation function ${\textstyle f(x)=\max(0,x)}$ .
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It effectively removes negative values from an activation map by setting them to zero.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It introduces nonlinearity to the decision function and in the overall network without affecting the receptive fields of the convolution layers.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, Xavier Glorot, Antoine Bordes and Yoshua Bengio found that ReLU enables better training of deeper networks, compared to widely used activation functions prior to 2011.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Other functions can also be used to increase nonlinearity, for example the saturating hyperbolic tangent $f(x)=\tanh(x)$ , $f(x)=|\tanh(x)|$ , and the sigmoid function ${\textstyle \sigma (x)=(1+e^{-x})^{-1}}$ .
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU is often preferred to other functions because it trains the neural network several times faster without a significant penalty to generalization accuracy.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] After several convolutional and max pooling layers, the final classification is done via fully connected layers.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Neurons in a fully connected layer have connections to all activations in the previous layer, as seen in regular (non-convolutional) artificial neural networks.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their activations can thus be computed as an affine transformation, with matrix multiplication followed by a bias offset (vector addition of a learned or fixed bias term).
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "loss layer", or "loss function", exemplifies how training penalizes the deviation between the predicted output of the network, and the true data labels (during supervised learning).
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Various loss functions can be used, depending on the specific task.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The Softmax loss function is used for predicting a single class of *K* mutually exclusive classes.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Sigmoid cross-entropy loss is used for predicting *K* independent probability values in $[0,1]$ .
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Euclidean loss is used for regressing to real-valued labels $(-\infty ,\infty )$ .
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Hyperparameters are various settings that are used to control the learning process.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use more hyperparameters than a standard multilayer perceptron (MLP).
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Padding is the addition of (typically) 0-valued pixels on the borders of an image.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is done so that the border pixels are not undervalued (lost) from the output because they would ordinarily participate in only a single receptive field instance.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The padding applied is typically one less than the corresponding kernel dimension.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a convolutional layer using 3x3 kernels would receive a 2-pixel pad, that is 1 pixel on each side of the image.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The stride is the number of pixels that the analysis window moves on each iteration.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A stride of 2 means that each kernel is offset by 2 pixels from its predecessor.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since feature map size decreases with depth, layers near the input layer tend to have fewer filters while higher layers can have more.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To equalize computation at each layer, the product of feature values *va* with pixel position is kept roughly constant across layers.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Preserving more information about the input would require keeping the total number of activations (number of feature maps times number of pixel positions) non-decreasing from one layer to the next.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The number of feature maps directly controls the capacity and depends on the number of available examples and task complexity.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Common filter sizes found in the literature vary greatly, and are usually chosen based on the data set.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Typical filter sizes range from 1x1 to 7x7.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As two famous examples, AlexNet used 3x3, 5x5, and 11x11.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The challenge is to find the right level of granularity so as to create abstractions at the proper scale, given a particular data set, and without overfitting.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Max pooling is typically used, often with a 2x2 dimension.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This implies that the input is drastically downsampled, reducing processing cost.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Greater pooling reduces the dimension of the signal, and may result in unacceptable information loss.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Often, non-overlapping pooling windows perform best.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Dilation involves ignoring pixels within a kernel.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This reduces processing memory potentially without significant signal loss.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A dilation of 2 on a 3x3 kernel expands the kernel to 5x5, while still processing 9 (evenly spaced) pixels.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Accordingly, dilation of 4 expands the kernel to 7x7.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is commonly assumed that CNNs are invariant to shifts of the input.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolution or pooling layers within a CNN that do not have a stride greater than one are indeed equivariant to translations of the input.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Furthermore, if a CNN makes use of fully connected layers, translation equivariance does not imply translation invariance, as the fully connected layers are not invariant to shifts of the input.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One solution for complete translation invariance is avoiding any down-sampling throughout the network and applying global average pooling at the last layer.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Additionally, several other partial solutions have been proposed, such as anti-aliasing before downsampling operations, spatial transformer networks, data augmentation, subsampling combined with pooling, and capsule neural networks.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The accuracy of the final model is typically estimated on a sub-part of the dataset set apart at the start, often called a test set.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Alternatively, methods such as *k*-fold cross-validation are applied.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Other strategies include using conformal prediction.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Regularization is a process of introducing additional information to solve an ill-posed problem or to prevent overfitting.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use various types of regularization.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because networks have so many parameters, they are prone to overfitting.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One method to reduce overfitting is dropout, introduced in 2014.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] At each training stage, individual nodes are either "dropped out" of the net (ignored) with probability $1-p$ or kept with probability p , so that a reduced network is left; incoming and outgoing edges to a dropped-out node are also removed.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Only the reduced network is trained on the data in that stage.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The removed nodes are then reinserted into the network with their original weights.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the training stages, p is usually 0.5; for input nodes, it is typically much higher because information is directly lost when input nodes are ignored.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] At testing time after training has finished, we would ideally like to find a sample average of all possible $2^{n}$ dropped-out networks; unfortunately this is unfeasible for large values of n .
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, we can find an approximation by using the full network with each node's output weighted by a factor of p , so the expected value of the output of any node is the same as in the training stages.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is the biggest contribution of the dropout method: although it effectively generates $2^{n}$ neural nets, and as such allows for model combination, at test time only a single network needs to be tested.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] By avoiding training all nodes on all training data, dropout decreases overfitting.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The method also significantly improves training speed.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This makes the model combination practical, even for deep neural networks.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The technique seems to reduce node interactions, leading them to learn more robust features that better generalize to new data.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] DropConnect is the generalization of dropout in which each connection, rather than each output unit, can be dropped with probability $1-p$ .
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each unit thus receives input from a random subset of units in the previous layer.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] DropConnect is similar to dropout as it introduces dynamic sparsity within the model, but differs in that the sparsity is on the weights, rather than the output vectors of a layer.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, the fully connected layer with DropConnect becomes a sparsely connected layer in which the connections are chosen at random during the training stage.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A major drawback to dropout is that it does not have the same benefits for convolutional layers, where the neurons are not fully connected.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This approach is free of hyperparameters and can be combined with other regularization approaches, such as dropout and data augmentation.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] An alternate view of stochastic pooling is that it is equivalent to standard max pooling but with many copies of an input image, each having small local deformations.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is similar to explicit elastic deformations of the input images, which delivers excellent performance on the MNIST data set.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Using stochastic pooling in a multilayer model gives an exponential number of deformations since the selections in higher layers are independent of those below.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because the degree of model overfitting is determined by both its power and the amount of training it receives, providing a convolutional network with more training examples can reduce overfitting.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because there is often not enough available data to train, especially considering that some part should be spared for later testing, two approaches are to either generate new data from scratch (if possible) or perturb existing data to create new ones.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, input images can be cropped, rotated, or rescaled to create new examples with the same labels as the original training set.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One of the simplest methods to prevent overfitting of a network is to simply stop the training before overfitting has had a chance to occur.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It comes with the disadvantage that the learning process is halted.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another simple way to prevent overfitting is to limit the number of parameters, typically by limiting the number of hidden units in each layer or limiting network depth.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For convolutional networks, the filter size also affects the number of parameters.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Limiting the number of parameters restricts the predictive power of the network directly, reducing the complexity of the function that it can perform on the data, and thus limits the amount of overfitting.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A simple form of added regularizer is weight decay, which simply adds an additional error, proportional to the sum of weights (L1 norm) or squared magnitude (L2 norm) of the weight vector, to the error at each node.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The level of acceptable model complexity can be reduced by increasing the proportionality constant('alpha' hyperparameter), thus increasing the penalty for large weight vectors.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] L2 regularization is the most common form of regularization.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It can be implemented by penalizing the squared magnitude of all parameters directly in the objective.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The L2 regularization has the intuitive interpretation of heavily penalizing peaky weight vectors and preferring diffuse weight vectors.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Due to multiplicative interactions between weights and inputs this has the useful property of encouraging the network to use all of its inputs a little rather than some of its inputs a lot.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It makes the weight vectors sparse during optimization.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, neurons with L1 regularization end up using only a sparse subset of their most important inputs and become nearly invariant to the noisy inputs.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] L1 with L2 regularization can be combined; this is called elastic net regularization.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another form of regularization is to enforce an absolute upper bound on the magnitude of the weight vector for every neuron and use projected gradient descent to enforce the constraint.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In practice, this corresponds to performing the parameter update as normal, and then enforcing the constraint by clamping the weight vector ${\vec {w}}$ of every neuron to satisfy $\|{\vec {w}}\|_{2}<c$ .
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Some papers report improvements when using this form of regularization.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Pooling loses the precise spatial relationships between high-level parts (such as nose and mouth in a face image).
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] These relationships are needed for identity recognition.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Overlapping the pools so that each feature occurs in multiple pools, helps retain the information.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Translation alone cannot extrapolate the understanding of geometric relationships to a radically new viewpoint, such as a different orientation or scale.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] On the other hand, people are very good at extrapolating; after seeing a new shape once they can recognize it from a different viewpoint.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] An earlier common way to deal with this problem is to train the network on transformed data in different orientations, scales, lighting, etc. so that the network can cope with these variations.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This is computationally intensive for large data-sets.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The alternative is to use a hierarchy of coordinate frames and use a group of neurons to represent a conjunction of the shape of the feature and its pose relative to the retina.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The pose relative to the retina is the relationship between the coordinate frame of the retina and the intrinsic features' coordinate frame.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Thus, one way to represent something is to embed the coordinate frame within it.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This allows large features to be recognized by using the consistency of the poses of their parts (e.g. nose and mouth poses make a consistent prediction of the pose of the whole face).
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This approach ensures that the higher-level entity (e.g. face) is present when the lower-level (e.g. nose and mouth) agree on its prediction of the pose.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The vectors of neuronal activity that represent pose ("pose vectors") allow spatial transformations modeled as linear operations that make it easier for the network to learn the hierarchy of visual entities and generalize across viewpoints.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This is similar to the way the human visual system imposes coordinate frames in order to represent shapes.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs are often used in image recognition systems.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2012, an error rate of 0.23% on the MNIST database was reported.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another paper on using CNN for image classification reported that the learning process was "surprisingly fast"; in the same paper, the best published results as of 2011 were achieved in the MNIST database and the NORB database.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Subsequently, a similar CNN called AlexNet won the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge 2012.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] When applied to facial recognition, CNNs achieved a large decrease in error rate.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another paper reported a 97.6% recognition rate on "5,600 still images of more than 10 subjects".
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs were used to assess video quality in an objective way after manual training; the resulting system had a very low root mean square error.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge is a benchmark in object classification and detection, with millions of images and hundreds of object classes.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In the ILSVRC 2014, a large-scale visual recognition challenge, almost every highly ranked team used CNN as their basic framework.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The winner GoogLeNet (the foundation of DeepDream) increased the mean average precision of object detection to 0.439329, and reduced classification error to 0.06656, the best result to date.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Its network applied more than 30 layers.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] That performance of convolutional neural networks on the ImageNet tests was close to that of humans.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The best algorithms still struggle with objects that are small or thin, such as a small ant on a stem of a flower or a person holding a quill in their hand.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They also have trouble with images that have been distorted with filters, an increasingly common phenomenon with modern digital cameras.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] By contrast, those kinds of images rarely trouble humans.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Humans, however, tend to have trouble with other issues.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] For example, they are not good at classifying objects into fine-grained categories such as the particular breed of dog or species of bird, whereas convolutional neural networks handle this.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2015, a many-layered CNN demonstrated the ability to spot faces from a wide range of angles, including upside down, even when partially occluded, with competitive performance.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The network was trained on a database of 200,000 images that included faces at various angles and orientations and a further 20 million images without faces.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They used batches of 128 images over 50,000 iterations.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Compared to image data domains, there is relatively little work on applying CNNs to video classification.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Video is more complex than images since it has another (temporal) dimension.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] However, some extensions of CNNs into the video domain have been explored.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] One approach is to treat space and time as equivalent dimensions of the input and perform convolutions in both time and space.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another way is to fuse the features of two convolutional neural networks, one for the spatial and one for the temporal stream.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Long short-term memory (LSTM) recurrent units are typically incorporated after the CNN to account for inter-frame or inter-clip dependencies.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Unsupervised learning schemes for training spatio-temporal features have been introduced, based on convolutional gated restricted Boltzmann machines and independent subspace analysis.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Its application can be seen in text-to-video models.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have also been explored for natural language processing.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNN models are effective for various NLP problems and achieved excellent results in semantic parsing, search query retrieval, sentence modeling, classification, prediction and other traditional NLP tasks.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Compared to traditional language processing methods such as recurrent neural networks, CNNs can represent different contextual realities of language that do not rely on a series-sequence assumption, while RNNs are better suitable when classical time series modeling is required.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have been applied in ecological and behavioral research to automatically detect and quantify animal behavior from visual data, enabling identification of animals, tracking of individuals, estimation of pose, and classification of specific actions such as feeding, and social interactions.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Combined with multi-object tracking and temporal modeling, these systems can extract behavioral sequences over extended recordings, reducing reliance on manual annotation and increasing throughput for studies of individual variation, social networks, and collective dynamics.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A CNN with 1-D convolutions was used on time series in the frequency domain (spectral residual) by an unsupervised model to detect anomalies in the time domain.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Predicting the interaction between molecules and biological proteins can identify potential treatments.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2015, Atomwise introduced AtomNet, the first deep learning neural network for structure-based drug design.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The system trains directly on 3-dimensional representations of chemical interactions.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Similar to how image recognition networks learn to compose smaller, spatially proximate features into larger, complex structures, AtomNet discovers chemical features, such as aromaticity, sp3 carbons, and hydrogen bonding.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Subsequently, AtomNet was used to predict novel candidate biomolecules for multiple disease targets, most notably treatments for the Ebola virus and multiple sclerosis.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have been used in the game of checkers.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] From 1999 to 2001, Fogel and Chellapilla published papers showing how a convolutional neural network could learn to play checkers using co-evolution.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The learning process did not use prior human professional games, but rather focused on a minimal set of information contained in the checkerboard: the location and type of pieces, and the difference in number of pieces between the two sides.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Ultimately, the program (Blondie24) was tested on 165 games against players and ranked in the highest 0.4%.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] It also earned a win against the program Chinook at its "expert" level of play.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In December 2014, Clark and Storkey published a paper showing that a CNN trained by supervised learning from a database of human professional games could outperform GNU Go and win some games against Monte Carlo tree search Fuego 1.1 in a fraction of the time it took Fuego to play.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Later it was announced that a large 12-layer convolutional neural network had correctly predicted the professional move in 55% of positions, equalling the accuracy of a 6 dan human player.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A couple of CNNs for choosing moves to try ("policy network") and evaluating positions ("value network") driving MCTS were used by AlphaGo, the first to beat the best human player at the time.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Recurrent neural networks are generally considered the best neural network architectures for time series forecasting (and sequence modeling in general), but recent studies show that convolutional networks can perform comparably or even better.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Dilated convolutions might enable one-dimensional convolutional neural networks to effectively learn time series dependences.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutions can be implemented more efficiently than RNN-based solutions, and they do not suffer from vanishing (or exploding) gradients.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional networks can provide an improved forecasting performance when there are multiple similar time series to learn from.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs can also be applied to further tasks in time series analysis (e.g., time series classification or quantile forecasting).
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] As archaeological findings such as clay tablets with cuneiform writing are increasingly acquired using 3D scanners, benchmark datasets are becoming available, including *HeiCuBeDa* providing almost 2000 normalized 2-D and 3-D datasets prepared with the GigaMesh Software Framework.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] So curvature-based measures are used in conjunction with geometric neural networks (GNNs), e.g. for period classification of those clay tablets being among the oldest documents of human history.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] For many applications, training data is not very available.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional neural networks usually require a large amount of training data in order to avoid overfitting.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A common technique is to train the network on a larger data set from a related domain.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Once the network parameters have converged an additional training step is performed using the in-domain data to fine-tune the network weights, this is known as transfer learning.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Furthermore, this technique allows convolutional network architectures to successfully be applied to problems with tiny training sets.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] End-to-end training and prediction are common practice in computer vision.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] However, human interpretable explanations are required for critical systems such as self-driving cars.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] With recent advances in visual salience, spatial attention, and temporal attention, the most critical spatial regions/temporal instants could be visualized to justify the CNN predictions.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A deep Q-network (DQN) is a type of deep learning model that combines a deep neural network with Q-learning, a form of reinforcement learning.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Unlike earlier reinforcement learning agents, DQNs that utilize CNNs can learn directly from high-dimensional sensory inputs via reinforcement learning.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Preliminary results were presented in 2014, with an accompanying paper in February 2015.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The research described an application to Atari 2600 gaming.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Other deep reinforcement learning models preceded it.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional deep belief networks (CDBN) have structure very similar to convolutional neural networks and are trained similarly to deep belief networks.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Therefore, they exploit the 2D structure of images, like CNNs do, and make use of pre-training like deep belief networks.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They provide a generic structure that can be used in many image and signal processing tasks.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Benchmark results on standard image datasets like CIFAR have been obtained using CDBNs.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The feed-forward architecture of convolutional neural networks was extended in the neural abstraction pyramid by lateral and feedback connections.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The resulting recurrent convolutional network allows for the flexible incorporation of contextual information to iteratively resolve local ambiguities.
[src:machine-learning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In contrast to previous models, image-like outputs at the highest resolution were generated, e.g., for semantic segmentation, image reconstruction, and object localization tasks.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] In machine learning, **deep learning** (**DL**) focuses on utilizing multilayered neural networks to perform tasks such as classification, regression, and representation learning.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The field takes inspiration from biological neuroscience and revolves around stacking artificial neurons into layers and "training" them to process data.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The adjective "deep" refers to the use of multiple layers (ranging from three to several hundred or thousands) in the network.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Methods used can be supervised, semi-supervised or unsupervised.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Some common deep learning network architectures include fully connected networks, deep belief networks, recurrent neural networks, convolutional neural networks, generative adversarial networks, transformers, and neural radiance fields.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Early forms of neural networks were inspired by information processing and distributed communication nodes in biological systems, particularly the human brain.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] However, current neural networks do not intend to model the brain function of organisms, and are generally seen as low-quality models for that purpose.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Fundamentally, deep learning refers to a class of machine learning algorithms in which a hierarchy of layers is used to transform input data into a progressively more abstract and composite representation.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] For example, in an image recognition model, the raw input may be an image (represented as a tensor of pixels).
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The first representational layer may attempt to identify basic shapes such as lines and circles, the second layer may compose and encode arrangements of edges, the third layer may encode a nose and eyes, and the fourth layer may recognize that the image contains a face.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Importantly, a deep learning process can learn which features to optimally place at which level *on its own*.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Prior to deep learning, machine learning techniques often involved hand-crafted feature engineering to transform the data into a more suitable representation for a classification algorithm to operate on.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] In the deep learning approach, features are not hand-crafted and the model discovers useful feature representations from the data automatically.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] This does not eliminate the need for hand-tuning; for example, varying numbers of layers and layer sizes can provide different degrees of abstraction.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The word "deep" in "deep learning" refers to the number of layers through which the data is transformed.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] More precisely, deep learning systems have a substantial *credit assignment path* (CAP) depth.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The CAP is the chain of transformations from input to output.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] CAPs describe potentially causal connections between input and output.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] For a feedforward neural network, the depth of the CAPs is that of the network and is the number of hidden layers plus one (as the output layer is also parameterized).
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] For recurrent neural networks, in which a signal may propagate through a layer more than once, the CAP depth is potentially unlimited.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] No universally agreed-upon threshold of depth divides shallow learning from deep learning, but most researchers agree that deep learning involves CAP depth higher than two.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] CAP of depth two has been shown to be a universal approximator in the sense that it can emulate any function.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Beyond that, more layers do not add to the function approximator ability of the network.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Deep models (CAP > two) are able to extract better features than shallow models and hence, extra layers help in learning the features effectively.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning architectures can be constructed with a greedy layer-by-layer method.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning helps to disentangle these abstractions and pick out which features improve performance.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning algorithms can be applied to unsupervised learning tasks.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] This is an important benefit because unlabeled data is more abundant than labeled data.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Examples of deep structures that can be trained in an unsupervised manner are deep belief networks.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The term *deep learning* was introduced to the machine learning community by Rina Dechter in 1986, and to artificial neural networks by Igor Aizenberg and colleagues in 2000, in the context of Boolean threshold neurons.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The etymology of the term is more complicated.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Deep neural networks are generally interpreted in terms of the universal approximation theorem or probabilistic inference.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The classic universal approximation theorem concerns the capacity of feedforward neural networks with a single hidden layer of finite size to approximate continuous functions.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] In 1989, the first proof was published by George Cybenko for sigmoid activation functions and was generalised to feed-forward multi-layer architectures in 1991 by Kurt Hornik.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Recent work also showed that universal approximation also holds for non-bounded activation functions such as Kunihiko Fukushima's rectified linear unit.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The universal approximation theorem for deep neural networks concerns the capacity of networks with bounded width but the depth is allowed to grow.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The probabilistic interpretation derives from the field of machine learning.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] It features inference, as well as the optimization concepts of training and testing, related to fitting and generalization, respectively.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] More specifically, the probabilistic interpretation considers the activation nonlinearity as a cumulative distribution function.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The probabilistic interpretation led to the introduction of dropout as regularizer in neural networks.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The probabilistic interpretation was introduced by researchers including Hopfield, Widrow and Narendra and popularized in surveys such as the one by Bishop.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] There are two types of artificial neural network (ANN): feedforward neural network (FNN) or multilayer perceptron (MLP) and recurrent neural networks (RNN).
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] RNNs have cycles in their connectivity structure, whereas FNNs do not.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] In the 1920s, Wilhelm Lenz and Ernst Ising created the Ising model which is essentially a non-learning RNN architecture consisting of neuron-like threshold elements.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] In 1972, Shun'ichi Amari made this architecture adaptive.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] His learning RNN was republished by John Hopfield in 1982.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Other early recurrent neural networks were published by Kaoru Nakano in 1971.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Already in 1948, Alan Turing produced work on "Intelligent Machinery" that was not published in his lifetime, containing "ideas related to artificial evolution and learning RNNs".
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Frank Rosenblatt (1958) proposed the perceptron, an MLP with 3 layers: an input layer, a hidden layer with randomized weights that did not learn, and an output layer.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] He later published a 1962 book that also introduced variants and computer experiments, including a version with four-layer perceptrons "with adaptive preterminal networks" where the last two layers have learned weights (here he credits H.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Joseph (1960) "functionally equivalent to a variation of" this four-layer system (the book mentions Joseph over 30 times).
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Should Joseph therefore be considered the originator of proper adaptive multilayer perceptrons with learning hidden units?
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Unfortunately, the learning algorithm was not a functional one, and fell into oblivion.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The first working deep learning algorithm was the Group method of data handling, a method to train arbitrarily deep neural networks, published by Alexey Ivakhnenko and Lapa in 1965.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] They regarded it as a form of polynomial regression, or a generalization of Rosenblatt's perceptron to handle more complex, nonlinear, and hierarchical relationships.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] A 1971 paper described a deep network with eight layers trained by this method, which is based on layer by layer training through regression analysis.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Superfluous hidden units are pruned using a separate validation set.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Since the activation functions of the nodes are Kolmogorov-Gabor polynomials, these were also the first deep networks with multiplicative units or "gates".
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The first deep learning multilayer perceptron trained by stochastic gradient descent was published in 1967 by Shun'ichi Amari.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] In computer experiments conducted by Amari's student Saito, a five layer MLP with two modifiable layers learned internal representations to classify non-linearily separable pattern classes.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Subsequent developments in hardware and hyperparameter tunings have made end-to-end stochastic gradient descent the currently dominant training technique.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The rectifier has become the most popular activation function for deep learning.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning architectures for convolutional neural networks (CNNs) with convolutional layers and downsampling layers began with the Neocognitron introduced by Kunihiko Fukushima in 1979, though not trained by backpropagation.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The terminology "back-propagating errors" was actually introduced in 1962 by Rosenblatt, but he did not know how to implement this, although Henry J.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Kelley had a continuous precursor of backpropagation in 1960 in the context of control theory.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The modern form of backpropagation was first published in Seppo Linnainmaa's master thesis (1970).
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Paul Werbos applied backpropagation to neural networks in 1982 (his 1974 PhD thesis, reprinted in a 1994 book, did not yet describe the algorithm).
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Rumelhart et al. popularised backpropagation but did not cite the original work.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The time delay neural network (TDNN) was introduced in 1987 by Alex Waibel to apply CNN to phoneme recognition.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] In 1988, Wei Zhang applied a backpropagation-trained CNN to alphabet recognition.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] LeNet-5 (1998), a 7-level CNN by Yann LeCun et al., that classifies digits, was applied by several banks to recognize hand-written numbers on checks digitized in 32x32 pixel images.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Recurrent neural networks (RNN) were further developed in the 1980s.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Recurrence is used for sequence processing, and when a recurrent network is unrolled, it mathematically resembles a deep feedforward layer.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Consequently, they have similar properties and issues, and their developments had mutual influences.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] In RNN, two early influential works were the Jordan network (1986) and the Elman network (1990), which applied RNN to study problems in cognitive psychology.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] In the 1980s, backpropagation did not work well for deep learning with long credit assignment paths.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] To overcome this problem, in 1991, Jürgen Schmidhuber proposed a hierarchy of RNNs pre-trained one level at a time by self-supervised learning where each RNN tries to predict its own next input, which is the next unexpected input of the RNN below.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] This "neural history compressor" uses predictive coding to learn internal representations at multiple self-organizing time scales.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] This can substantially facilitate downstream deep learning.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The RNN hierarchy can be *collapsed* into a single RNN, by distilling a higher level *chunker* network into a lower level *automatizer* network.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] In 1993, a neural history compressor solved a "Very Deep Learning" task that required more than 1000 subsequent layers in an RNN unfolded in time.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The "P" in ChatGPT refers to such pre-training.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Sepp Hochreiter's diploma thesis (1991) implemented the neural history compressor, and identified and analyzed the vanishing gradient problem.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Hochreiter proposed recurrent residual connections to solve the vanishing gradient problem.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] This led to the long short-term memory (LSTM), published in 1995.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] LSTM can learn "very deep learning" tasks with long credit assignment paths that require memories of events that happened thousands of discrete time steps before.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] That LSTM was not yet the modern architecture, which required a "forget gate", introduced in 1999, which became the standard RNN architecture.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] In 1991, Jürgen Schmidhuber also published adversarial neural networks that contest with each other in the form of a zero-sum game, where one network's gain is the other network's loss.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] In 2014, this principle was used in generative adversarial networks (GANs).
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] During 1985–1995, inspired by statistical mechanics, several architectures and methods were developed by Terry Sejnowski, Peter Dayan, Geoffrey Hinton, etc., including the Boltzmann machine, restricted Boltzmann machine, Helmholtz machine, and the wake-sleep algorithm.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] However, those were more computationally expensive compared to backpropagation.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Boltzmann machine learning algorithm, published in 1985, was briefly popular before being eclipsed by the backpropagation algorithm in 1986.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] A 1988 network became state of the art in protein structure prediction, an early application of deep learning to bioinformatics.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Both shallow and deep learning (e.g., recurrent nets) of ANNs for speech recognition have been explored for many years.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] These methods never outperformed non-uniform internal-handcrafting Gaussian mixture model/Hidden Markov model (GMM-HMM) technology based on generative models of speech trained discriminatively.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Key difficulties have been analyzed, including gradient diminishing and weak temporal correlation structure in neural predictive models.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Additional difficulties were the lack of training data and limited computing power.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Most speech recognition researchers moved away from neural nets to pursue generative modeling.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] An exception was at SRI International in the late 1990s.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Funded by the US government's NSA and DARPA, SRI researched in speech and speaker recognition.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The speaker recognition team led by Larry Heck reported significant success with deep neural networks in speech processing in the 1998 NIST Speaker Recognition benchmark.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] It was deployed in the Nuance Verifier, representing the first major industrial application of deep learning.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The raw features of speech, waveforms, later produced excellent larger-scale results.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] In 2003, LSTM became competitive with traditional speech recognizers on certain tasks.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] In 2006, Alex Graves, Santiago Fernández, Faustino Gomez, and Schmidhuber combined it with connectionist temporal classification (CTC) in stacks of LSTMs.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] In 2009, it became the first RNN to win a pattern recognition contest, in connected handwriting recognition.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] In 2006, publications by Geoff Hinton, Ruslan Salakhutdinov, Osindero and Teh deep belief networks were developed for generative modeling.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] They are trained by training one restricted Boltzmann machine, then freezing it and training another one on top of the first one, and so on, then optionally fine-tuned using supervised backpropagation.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] They could model high-dimensional probability distributions, such as the distribution of MNIST images, but convergence was slow.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The impact of deep learning in industry began in the early 2000s, when CNNs already processed an estimated 10% to 20% of all the checks written in the US, according to Yann LeCun.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Industrial applications of deep learning to large-scale speech recognition started around 2010.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The 2009 NIPS Workshop on Deep Learning for Speech Recognition was motivated by the limitations of deep generative models of speech, and the possibility that given more capable hardware and large-scale data sets that deep neural nets might become practical.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] It was believed that pre-training DNNs using generative models of deep belief nets (DBN) would overcome the main difficulties of neural nets.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The nature of the recognition errors produced by the two types of systems was characteristically different, offering technical insights into how to integrate deep learning into the existing highly efficient, run-time speech decoding system deployed by all major speech recognition systems.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Analysis around 2009–2010, contrasting the GMM (and other generative speech models) vs.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] DNN models, stimulated early industrial investment in deep learning for speech recognition.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] That analysis was done with comparable performance (less than 1.5% in error rate) between discriminative DNNs and generative models.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] In 2010, researchers extended deep learning from TIMIT to large vocabulary speech recognition, by adopting large output layers of the DNN based on context-dependent HMM states constructed by decision trees.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The deep learning revolution started around CNN- and GPU-based computer vision.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Although CNNs trained by backpropagation had been around for decades and GPU implementations of NNs for years, including CNNs, faster implementations of CNNs on GPUs were needed to progress on computer vision.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Later, as deep learning becomes widespread, specialized hardware and algorithm optimizations were developed specifically for deep learning.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] A key advance for the deep learning revolution was hardware advances, especially GPU.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] In 2009, Raina, Madhavan, and Andrew Ng reported a 100M deep belief network trained on 30 Nvidia GeForce GTX 280 GPUs, an early demonstration of GPU-based deep learning.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] They reported up to 70 times faster training.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] In 2011, a CNN named *DanNet* by Dan Ciresan, Ueli Meier, Jonathan Masci, Luca Maria Gambardella, and Jürgen Schmidhuber achieved for the first time superhuman performance in a visual pattern recognition contest, outperforming traditional methods by a factor of 3.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] They also showed how max-pooling CNNs on GPU improved performance significantly.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] In 2012, Andrew Ng and Jeff Dean created an FNN that learned to recognize higher-level concepts, such as cats, only from watching unlabeled images taken from YouTube videos.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] In October 2012, AlexNet by Alex Krizhevsky, Ilya Sutskever, and Geoffrey Hinton won the large-scale ImageNet competition by a significant margin over shallow machine learning methods.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The success in image classification was then extended to the more challenging task of generating descriptions (captions) for images, often as a combination of CNNs and LSTMs.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] In 2014, the state of the art was training "very deep neural network" with 20 to 30 layers.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] In 2015, two techniques were developed to train very deep networks: the highway network was published in May 2015, and the residual neural network (ResNet) in Dec 2015.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Around the same time, deep learning started impacting the field of art.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Early examples included Google DeepDream (2015), and neural style transfer (2015), both of which were based on pretrained image classification neural networks, such as VGG-19.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Generative adversarial network (GAN) by (Ian Goodfellow et al., 2014) (based on Jürgen Schmidhuber's principle of artificial curiosity) became state of the art in generative modeling during 2014-2018 period.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Excellent image quality is achieved by Nvidia's StyleGAN (2018) based on the Progressive GAN by Tero Karras et al.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Here the GAN generator is grown from small to large scale in a pyramidal fashion.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Diffusion models (2015) eclipsed GANs in generative modeling since then, with systems such as DALL·E 2 (2022) and Stable Diffusion (2022).
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] In 2015, Google's speech recognition improved by 49% by an LSTM-based model, which they made available through Google Voice Search on smartphone.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning is part of state-of-the-art systems in various disciplines, particularly computer vision and automatic speech recognition (ASR).
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Results on commonly used evaluation sets such as TIMIT (ASR) and MNIST (image classification), as well as a range of large-vocabulary speech recognition tasks have steadily improved.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Convolutional neural networks were superseded for ASR by LSTM. but are more successful in computer vision.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Yoshua Bengio, Geoffrey Hinton and Yann LeCun were awarded the 2018 Turing Award for "conceptual and engineering breakthroughs that have made deep neural networks a critical component of computing".
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] An ANN is based on a collection of connected units called artificial neurons, (analogous to biological neurons in a biological brain).
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Each connection (synapse) between neurons can transmit a signal to another neuron.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The receiving (postsynaptic) neuron can process the signal(s) and then signal downstream neurons connected to it.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Neurons may have state, generally represented by real numbers, typically between 0 and 1.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Neurons and synapses may also have a weight that varies as learning proceeds, which can increase or decrease the strength of the signal that it sends downstream.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Typically, neurons are organized in layers.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Different layers may perform different kinds of transformations on their inputs.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Signals travel from the first (input), to the last (output) layer, possibly after traversing the layers multiple times.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The original goal of the neural network approach was to solve problems in the same way that a human brain would.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Over time, attention focused on matching specific mental abilities, leading to deviations from biology such as backpropagation, or passing information in the reverse direction and adjusting the network to reflect that information.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Neural networks have been used on a variety of tasks, including computer vision, speech recognition, machine translation, social network filtering, playing board and video games and medical diagnosis.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] As of 2017, neural networks typically have a few thousand to a few million units and millions of connections.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Despite this number being several order of magnitude less than the number of neurons on a human brain, these networks can perform many tasks at a level beyond that of humans (e.g., recognizing faces, or playing "Go").
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] A **deep neural network** (**DNN**) is an artificial neural network with multiple layers between the input and output layers.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] There are different types of neural networks but they always consist of the same components: neurons, synapses, weights, biases, and functions.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] These components as a whole function in a way that mimics functions of the human brain, and can be trained like any other ML algorithm.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] For example, a DNN that is trained to recognize dog breeds will go over the given image and calculate the probability that the dog in the image is a certain breed.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The user can review the results and select which probabilities the network should display (above a certain threshold, etc.) and return the proposed label.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Each mathematical manipulation as such is considered a layer, and complex DNN have many layers, hence the name "deep" networks.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] DNNs can model complex non-linear relationships.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] DNN architectures generate compositional models where the object is expressed as a layered composition of primitives.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The extra layers enable composition of features from lower layers, potentially modeling complex data with fewer units than a similarly performing shallow network.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] For instance, it was proved that sparse multivariate polynomials are exponentially easier to approximate with DNNs than with shallow networks.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Deep architectures include many variants of a few basic approaches.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Each architecture has found success in specific domains.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] It is not always possible to compare the performance of multiple architectures, unless they have been evaluated on the same data sets.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] DNNs are typically feedforward networks in which data flows from the input layer to the output layer without looping back.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] At first, the DNN creates a map of virtual neurons and assigns random numerical values, or "weights", to connections between them.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The weights and inputs are multiplied and return an output between 0 and 1.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] If the network did not accurately recognize a particular pattern, an algorithm would adjust the weights.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] That way the algorithm can make certain parameters more influential, until it determines the correct mathematical manipulation to fully process the data.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Recurrent neural networks, in which data can flow in any direction, are used for applications such as language modeling.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Long short-term memory is particularly effective for this use.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Convolutional neural networks (CNNs) are used in computer vision.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] CNNs also have been applied to acoustic modeling for automatic speech recognition (ASR).
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] As with ANNs, many issues can arise with naively trained DNNs.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Two common issues are overfitting and computation time.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] DNNs are prone to overfitting because of the added layers of abstraction, which allow them to model rare dependencies in the training data.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Regularization methods such as Ivakhnenko's unit pruning or weight decay ( $\ell _{2}$ -regularization) or sparsity ( $\ell _{1}$ -regularization) can be applied during training to combat overfitting.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Alternatively dropout regularization randomly omits units from the hidden layers during training.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] This helps to exclude rare dependencies.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Another interesting recent development is research into models of just enough complexity through an estimation of the intrinsic complexity of the task being modelled.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] This approach has been successfully applied for multivariate time series prediction tasks such as traffic prediction.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Finally, data can be augmented via methods such as cropping and rotating such that smaller training sets can be increased in size to reduce the chances of overfitting.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] DNNs must consider many training parameters, such as the size (number of layers and number of units per layer), the learning rate, and initial weights.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Sweeping through the parameter space for optimal parameters may not be feasible due to the cost in time and computational resources.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Various tricks, such as batching (computing the gradient on several training examples at once rather than individual examples) speed up computation.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Large processing capabilities of many-core architectures (such as GPUs or the Intel Xeon Phi) have produced significant speedups in training, because of the suitability of such processing architectures for the matrix and vector computations.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Alternatively, engineers may look for other types of neural networks with more straightforward and convergent training algorithms.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] CMAC (cerebellar model articulation controller) is one such kind of neural network.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] It doesn't require learning rates or randomized initial weights.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The training process can be guaranteed to converge in one step with a new batch of data, and the computational complexity of the training algorithm is linear with respect to the number of neurons involved.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Since the 2010s, advances in both machine learning algorithms and computer hardware have led to more efficient methods for training deep neural networks that contain many layers of non-linear hidden units and a very large output layer.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] By 2019, graphics processing units (GPUs), often with AI-specific enhancements, had displaced CPUs as the dominant method for training large-scale commercial cloud AI .
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] OpenAI estimated the hardware computation used in the largest deep learning projects from AlexNet (2012) to AlphaZero (2017) and found a 300,000-fold increase in the amount of computation required, with a doubling-time trendline of 3.4 months.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Special electronic circuits called deep learning processors were designed to speed up deep learning algorithms.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning processors include neural processing units (NPUs) in Huawei cellphones and cloud computing servers such as tensor processing units (TPU) in the Google Cloud Platform.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Cerebras Systems has also built a dedicated system to handle large deep learning models, the CS-2, based on the largest processor in the industry, the second-generation Wafer Scale Engine (WSE-2).
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Atomically thin semiconductors are considered promising for energy-efficient deep learning hardware where the same basic device structure is used for both logic operations and data storage.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] In 2020, Marega et al. published experiments with a large-area active channel material for developing logic-in-memory devices and circuits based on floating-gate field-effect transistors (FGFETs).
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Feldmann et al. proposed an integrated photonic hardware accelerator for parallel convolutional processing.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] The authors identify two key advantages of integrated photonics over its electronic counterparts: (1) massively parallel data transfer through wavelength division multiplexing in conjunction with frequency combs, and (2) extremely high data modulation speeds.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p01] Their system can execute trillions of multiply-accumulate operations per second, indicating the potential of integrated photonics in data-heavy AI applications.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Large-scale automatic speech recognition is the first and most convincing successful case of deep learning.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] LSTM RNNs can learn "Very Deep Learning" tasks that involve multi-second intervals containing speech events separated by thousands of discrete time steps, where one time step corresponds to about 10 ms.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] LSTM with forget gates is competitive with traditional speech recognizers on certain tasks.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] The initial success in speech recognition was based on small-scale recognition tasks based on TIMIT.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] The data set contains 630 speakers from eight major dialects of American English, where each speaker reads 10 sentences.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Its small size lets many configurations be tried.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] More importantly, the TIMIT task concerns phone-sequence recognition, which, unlike word-sequence recognition, allows weak phone bigram language models.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] This lets the strength of the acoustic modeling aspects of speech recognition be more easily analyzed.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] The error rates listed below, including these early results and measured as percent phone error rates (PER), have been summarized since 1991.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] More recent speech recognition models use Transformers or Temporal Convolution Networks with significant success and widespread applications.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] All major commercial speech recognition systems (e.g., Microsoft Cortana, Xbox, Skype Translator, Amazon Alexa, Google Now, Apple Siri, Baidu and iFlyTek voice search, and a range of Nuance speech products, etc.) are based on deep learning.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] A common evaluation set for image classification is the MNIST database data set.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] MNIST is composed of handwritten digits and includes 60,000 training examples and 10,000 test examples.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] As with TIMIT, its small size lets users test multiple configurations.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] A comprehensive list of results on this set is available.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning-based image recognition has become "superhuman", producing more accurate results than human contestants.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] This first occurred in 2011 in recognition of traffic signs, and in 2014, with recognition of human faces.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning-trained vehicles now interpret 360° camera views.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Another example is Facial Dysmorphology Novel Analysis (FDNA) used to analyze cases of human malformation connected to a large database of genetic syndromes.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Closely related to the progress that has been made in image recognition is the increasing application of deep learning techniques to various visual art tasks.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Neural networks have been used for implementing language models since the early 2000s.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] LSTM helped to improve machine translation and language modeling.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Other key techniques in this field are negative sampling and word embedding.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Word embedding, such as *word2vec*, can be thought of as a representational layer in a deep learning architecture that transforms an atomic word into a positional representation of the word relative to other words in the dataset; the position is represented as a point in a vector space.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Using word embedding as an RNN input layer allows the network to parse sentences and phrases using an effective compositional vector grammar.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] A compositional vector grammar can be thought of as probabilistic context free grammar (PCFG) implemented by an RNN.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Recursive auto-encoders built atop word embeddings can assess sentence similarity and detect paraphrasing.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Recent developments generalize word embedding to sentence embedding.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Google Translate (GT) uses a large end-to-end long short-term memory (LSTM) network.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Google Neural Machine Translation (GNMT) uses an example-based machine translation method in which the system "learns from millions of examples".
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] It translates "whole sentences at a time, rather than pieces".
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Google Translate supports over one hundred languages.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] The network encodes the "semantics of the sentence rather than simply memorizing phrase-to-phrase translations".
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] GT uses English as an intermediate between most language pairs.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] A large percentage of candidate drugs fail to win regulatory approval.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] These failures are caused by insufficient efficacy (on-target effect), undesired interactions (off-target effects), or unanticipated toxic effects.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Research has explored use of deep learning to predict the biomolecular targets, off-targets, and toxic effects of environmental chemicals in nutrients, household products and drugs.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] AtomNet is a deep learning system for structure-based rational drug design.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] AtomNet was used to predict novel candidate biomolecules for disease targets such as the Ebola virus and multiple sclerosis.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] In 2017 graph neural networks were used for the first time to predict various properties of molecules in a large toxicology data set.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] In 2019, generative neural networks were used to produce molecules that were validated experimentally all the way into mice.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Recommendation systems have used deep learning to extract meaningful features for a latent factor model for content-based music and journal recommendations.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Multi-view deep learning has been applied for learning user preferences from multiple domains.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] The model uses a hybrid collaborative and content-based approach and enhances recommendations in multiple tasks.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] An autoencoder ANN was used in bioinformatics, to predict gene ontology annotations and gene-function relationships.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] In medical informatics, deep learning was used to predict sleep quality based on data from wearables and predictions of health complications from electronic health record data.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Deep neural networks have shown unparalleled performance in predicting protein structure, according to the sequence of the amino acids that make it up.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] In 2020, AlphaFold, a deep-learning based system, achieved a level of accuracy significantly higher than all previous computational methods.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Deep neural networks can be used to estimate the entropy of a stochastic process through an arrangement called a Neural Joint Entropy Estimator (NJEE).
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Such an estimation provides insights on the effects of input random variables on an independent random variable.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Practically, the DNN is trained as a classifier that maps an input vector or matrix X to an output probability distribution over the possible classes of random variable Y, given input X.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] For example, in image classification tasks, the NJEE maps a vector of pixels' color values to probabilities over possible image classes.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] In practice, the probability distribution of Y is obtained by a Softmax layer with number of nodes that is equal to the alphabet size of Y.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] NJEE uses continuously differentiable activation functions, such that the conditions for the universal approximation theorem holds.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] It is shown that this method provides a strongly consistent estimator and outperforms other methods in cases of large alphabet sizes.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has been shown to produce competitive results in medical applications such as cancer cell classification, lesion detection, organ segmentation and image enhancement.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Modern deep learning tools demonstrate the high accuracy of detecting various diseases and the helpfulness of their use by specialists to improve the diagnosis efficiency.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Finding the appropriate mobile audience for mobile advertising is always challenging, since many data points must be considered and analyzed before a target segment can be created and used in ad serving by any ad server.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has been used to interpret large, many-dimensioned advertising datasets.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Many data points are collected during the request/serve/click internet advertising cycle.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] This information can form the basis of machine learning to improve ad selection.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has been successfully applied to inverse problems such as denoising, super-resolution, inpainting, and film colorization.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] These applications include learning methods such as "Shrinkage Fields for Effective Image Restoration" which trains on an image dataset, and Deep Image Prior, which trains on the image that needs restoration.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning is being applied to financial fraud detection, tax evasion detection, and anti-money laundering.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] In November 2023, researchers at Google DeepMind and Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory announced that they had developed an AI system known as GNoME.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] This system has contributed to materials science by discovering over 2 million new materials within a relatively short timeframe.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] GNoME employs deep learning techniques to efficiently explore potential material structures, achieving a significant increase in the identification of stable inorganic crystal structures.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] The system's predictions were validated through autonomous robotic experiments, demonstrating a noteworthy success rate of 71%.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] The data of newly discovered materials is publicly available through the Materials Project database, offering researchers the opportunity to identify materials with desired properties for various applications.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] This development has implications for the future of scientific discovery and the integration of AI in material science research, potentially expediting material innovation and reducing costs in product development.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] The use of AI and deep learning suggests the possibility of minimizing or eliminating manual lab experiments and allowing scientists to focus more on the design and analysis of unique compounds.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] The United States Department of Defense applied deep learning to train robots in new tasks through observation.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Physics-informed neural networks have been used to solve partial differential equations in both forward and inverse problems in a data driven manner.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] One example is the reconstructing fluid flow governed by the Navier-Stokes equations.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] Using physics informed neural networks does not require the often expensive mesh generation that conventional CFD methods rely on.
[src:machine-learning/deep-learning-p02] It is evident that geometric and physical constraints have a synergistic effect on neural PDE surrogates, thereby enhancing their efficacy in predicting stable and super long rollouts.
